<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--SmokingBan     07-09 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Smoking Ban,0130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Punishment For Smokers Violating Norway's Anti-Smoking Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smokers will not be punished for violating
Norway's tough new anti-smoking law, a government official said.
   But operators of restaurants, hotels or other public areas risk
fines if people are found smoking where they shouldn't, Trine Lind,
information secretary of the Social Ministry said Friday.
   The law went into effect July 1, but its provisions were only
set at a cabinet meeting on Friday. Maximum fines were not
immediately published.
   The law bans smoking outside special smoking sections in public
transportion, theater lobbies, banks, post offices and work places.
   The government has said it wants to make Norway tobacco-free by
the year 2000. Four out of 10 adult Norwegians now smoke.
</TEXT>
