<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Koch     07-09 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Koch,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pirates-Mets Rivalry Has Mayors Crossing Swords</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward Koch told the Pittsburgh Pirates
they'll walk the plank in their next series with the New York Mets,
in another inning _ er, round _ of good-natured goading between
Pittsburgh and New York.
   When the Pirates ran a series of ads two weeks ago calling the
Mets another good reason to hate New York, Koch said of Pittsburgh,
``Where is it?''
   Pittsburgh Mayor Sophie Masloff sent Koch a map and reminded him
of Pittsburgh's considerable charms. And Koch, through a television
reporter, invited her to lunch in the Big Apple.
   Koch sent a letter Wednesday to Masloff saying he was
``delighted to learn that Pittsburgh has been designated one of
America's `most-livable cities.''' But the designation obviously
was made, Koch said, by someone ``with a sense of humor.''
   ``I can't promise your Buccaneers (the Pirates) will be walking
on a red carpet when they arrive in the Big Apple for their next
series with the Mets, but we will be looking for an appropriate
plank,'' Koch said.
   The Pirates will be at Shea Stadium for a four-game series
starting July 29. The Mets visit Three Rivers Stadium Aug. 5 for a
four-game meeting.
   Koch's office released his letter Friday, as well as a letter
sent June 30 by Masloff to Koch.
   Masloff wrote, ``While I felt your comment on Pittsburgh's
location was tongue in cheek _ Pittsburgh having been designated
America's most-livable city and being the third-largest corporate
headquarters in the nation _ just to be on the safe side, I am
sending you a map of Pittsburgh.
   ``It would be nice if you could make use of it when the Mets and
Pirates tangle here again,'' she added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
