<DOCNO> AP880709-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0028EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OilRig-Jumpers Bjt   07-09 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Rig-Jumpers, Bjt,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivors Describe Oil Rig Ordeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Rig, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-four men survived the Piper
Alpha oil rig fire by leaping into the burning sea in the dark, but
they had to leave behind more than 100 colleagues trapped and
screaming for air in the inferno.
   ``I am one of the lucky ones,'' Harry Calder said in an
interview Friday. ``I am pretty sore, I am badly bruised and my
hands are burned. But at least I'm alive. I have lost a lot of
friends.''
   Seventeen bodies have been found and 166 men are presumed dead
in the North Sea oil field where the rig exploded Wednesday night.
   At least 100 men died screaming for help, trapped in their
sleeping quarters after surviving the first explosion, said Calder,
a 35-year-old helicopter landing officer.
   The workers were in the smoke-filled galley of the platform,
which was plunged into darkness when the emergency lighting failed,
he said in an interview Friday.
   ``Windows and the emergency door were cracking under the intense
heat. There must have been at least 100 men in there,'' Calder
said. ``Men were shouting into their radios: `We need breathing
apparatus. What's happening? Is there anybody getting out? We are
all going to die.'
   ``It was sheer panic. A lot of guys were lying on the floor,
just trying to breathe. We had towels and we were just dipping them
in anything to help us breathe,'' he said.
   Calder and a co-worker got out through a rear door just in time,
he said, ``but I don't think the others made it. I would have
perished with them if I hadn't got out when I did.''
   He said he was asleep when the first explosion ripped through
the rig, but he and his colleague had climbed on to the roof of the
helicopter deck by the time the second blast hit. They made their
way to the pipe deck and lay under a steel table for protection.
   ``We were hardly getting any breath. It was really bad,'' he
said. ``Then, all of a sudden, the floor collapsed and we found
ourselves lying at an angle. We saw a clear view looking through
the smoke. We said rather than burn, we can get through that and
jump.
   ``We crawled along pipes which were scalding hot. I burned my
hands,'' he said. ``We got to the edge of the platform and just
jumped. It was well over 100 feet to the sea. I missed the flames
in the water.
   ``I didn't have a life jacket,'' Calder said. ``I hit the water
and came up and I was OK. I started swimming and kept swimming.''
   The two men got clear and Calder said he held onto his
co-worker's life jacket. ``Then a life jacket appeared on the water
in front of me and I put it on. It was a stroke of luck.
   ``There was debris everywhere and a lot of guys were sitting on
pieces of debris. The waves were coming over my head.
   ``Then I saw a supply boat. It was easily a mile away. I kept
swimming and swimming and waving and shouting. I wasn't sure
whether I had been seen.
   ``I was sure the skipper had given me a flash with his lights,
but the boat seemed to be going away,'' Calder said. ``I thought
that was going to be it _ that I was going to die.
   ``Then the boat went into reverse and turned round. It came to
me and threw me a lifeline. They pulled me aboard. My friend was
picked up by another vessel. I was told later that he was OK.''
   Another survivor, 50-year-old James McDonald, said that when he
and some others tried to leave the crew's quarters, ``the flames
were shooting into the doors. ... For about three-quarters of an
hour we were sitting inside. Nobody seemed to know what to do.''
   Fire spread rapidly, turning metal girders red-hot and bringing
decks crashing down in half-molten heaps.
   The men faced a hard choice: stay aboard and hope aid got to
them before the flames, or jump into a sea that was cold enough
below the burning oil to kill them. Even on a clear summer night,
the water temperature was 57 degrees.
   Burning oil was spreading across the few bare patches of water
remaining and the decision had to be made quickly.
   ``I decided to get myself out,'' McDonald said. ``I wasn't going
to sit down and get burned to death. ... You either stayed where
you were and burned to death or you tried to get out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
