<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile-Election     07-09 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Election,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Announces Presidential Vote Within 90 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALCAHUANO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President and military leader Augusto
Pinochet said a plebiscite to choose the president for 1989-97 will
take place within the next 90 days. He is expected to be the only
candidate.
   Pinochet also said Friday he already has a platform for his next
presidential term, but he refused to disclose it because the
opposition ``would copy it.''
   ``The plebiscite is near. There are less than 90 days left,''
Pinochet told an audience of 16,000 supporters in this southern
port city 330 miles from Santiago.
   The 72-year-old army commander has ruled this South American
nation since a 1973 coup. His remark was the most precise
indication so far of a date for the ballot.
   According to the 1980 military-drafted Constitution, the
nation's next presiddnt will be picked in a plebiscite in which
Chileans will only be able to vote yes or no on a single candidate
nominated by the heads of the three armed services and the national
police.
   Pinochet himself will participate in the nomination as
commander-in-chief of the army and is considered the most likely
nominee. He is allowed by the Constitution to seek re-election and
has clearly indicated he intends to do so.
   If voters approve the nominee, he will serve for eight years
starting in March 1989. If rejected, Pinochet will remain in power
until 1990, and an open election would take place.
   Pinochet blasted opposition leaders seeking support from the
international community as ``traitors.''
   He said some critics who recently were given limited access to
television are going too far in their broadscast remarks.
   ``When those bad Chileans make insults on television, because
they know we are in a democracy and we won't do anything to them,
let's tell them that our patience has limits and that they could
soon discover those limits,'' Pinochet warned.
   He predicted an overwhelming victory in the upcoming plebiscite
and said of his opponents, ``We will wipe them out.''
</TEXT>
