<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DramaticRescue     07-09 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dramatic Rescue,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Ship Officer Rescues Woman From Drowning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sylvie Mullaly and Lars Kragelund are cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NAN HERLIHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cruise ship officer stripped to his shorts and
leapt more than 50-feet into choppy night seas to rescue a drowning
woman, the Coast Guard said Friday.
   The woman either fell or jumped off the Scandinavian Sky cruise
ship 11 miles east of Cape Canaveral Thursday night, said Petty
Officer Tom Leyden.
   Sylvie Mullaly, 31, of Cocoa Beach, and her rescuer, Staff Capt.
Lars Kragelund, were treated and released from Cape Canaveral
Hospital following the ships return, the Coast Guard said.
   Mullaly, who works at a topless nightclub in Cocoa Beach, is
under investigation for possible intoxication, Leyden said. An
investigation of the entire incident, including the ship's safety
procedures, is underway, he said.
   Ms. Mullaly was spotted bobbing in the water as the ship
returned from a daylong cruise, Leyden said. Kragelund raced from
the ship's wheelhouse, peeling off his uniform as he ran and dived
from a ship's rail, he said.
   As he swam to the woman, the ship's crew assumed ``man
overboard'' alert stations and the vessel swung in a wide circle
around the couple, Leyden said.
   ``Apparently they were retrieved from the water via ladder. The
Coast Guard headed to the scene but turned back when we found out
they had her'' out of the water, he said.
   The Scandinavian Sky is owned by Miami-based Sea Escape Limited
and registered in Panama, according to Coast Guard reports.
</TEXT>
