<DOCNO> AP880709-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe Bjt   07-09 0956</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe, Bjt,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Looking Into Whether Paisley Took Bribes In Navy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Court papers have revealed for the first time
that federal agents are looking at whether one of the Navy's former
top officials accepted bribes while he helped direct President
Reagan's defense buildup.
   A search warrant used by the FBI in the June 14 search of
defense consultant Melvyn R. Paisley's home in nearby McLean, Va.,
said agents sought details about ``payment from General Dynamics
and McDonnell Douglas to Paisley in the form of checks, gifts or
other forms of remuneration, or to his wife, Vicki'' at the time he
was an assistant Navy secretary.
   Another entry states agents wanted information about ``payments
or gratuities from Pratt & Whitney employees to Paisley'' before he
left the Navy in March 1987. Pratt & Whitney is a division of
United Technologies Corp.
   As an assistant Navy secretary between 1981 and 1987, Paisley,
63, played a key role in guiding the enhancement of the Navy under
then-Navy Secretary John Lehman Jr. A former executive at the
Boeing Co., Paisley left government to become a consultant.
   Paisley has surfaced as a key figure in the investigation into
allegations that defense contractors and consultants, many of them
former military men, bribed Pentagon officials for contracting
details that could be vital in winning contracts worth billions of
dollars. To date, no one has been charged in the case.
   The Washington Post reported today that the unnamed informer
referred to in an early government affidavit who helped
investigators launch the probe is a retired Marine Corps major who
is now serving a prison sentence for child molestation.
   The Post, quoting unnamed sources, said consultant John P.
Marlowe offered inside information on Marine contracts to a defense
firm and later agreed to cooperate with government investigators
and secretly tape his conversations with other consultants.
   Marlowe, 45, is serving a six-year sentence at a Virginia state
prison for his 1985 conviction on charges of indecent exposure and
aggravated sexual battery in cases involving two girls aged nine
and 10, the Post reported.
   Paisley's house was one of as many as 40 premises across the
nation searched on June 14, the day the FBI revealed the existence
of the investigation of alleged massive corruption in the $150
billion-a-year Defense Department purchasing system.
   The search warrant, which was released by a magistrate's clerk
in U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va., said the FBI also sought
evidence that Paisley gave James E. Gaines, a deputy assistant
secretary of the Navy, a Western painting titled ``Lonesome
Whistle.''
   They also sought evidence that Paisley or fellow consultant
William Galvin provided gratuities to Gaines, including ``money to
Gaines' companies, entertainment tickets, and tires.''
   The FBI documents showed the government is investigating
Paisley's work as a consultant to 10 defense contractors and
disclosed the names of several Pentagon employees, or former
Pentagon employees, whose contacts with Paisley are being
investigated.
   The warrant sought any document ``establishing an employee or
contractual relationship'' between Paisley and these 10 companies:
McDonnell Douglas Corp., Martin Marietta, BDM, EMS, Pocal, Ball
Aerospace, United Technologies Corp., Norden, Unisys and Whittaker.
   Agents are looking at Paisley's efforts to obtain government
contracts for them from 1981 through 1988.
   Among the people mentioned specifically in the warrant was a
person identified as Rumpf.
   Richard R. Rumpf, the principal deputy assistant secretary of
the Navy for research, engineering and systems, was Paisley's
deputy in the Pentagon. His wife, Lenore, works for the Navy Air
Systems Command.
   Rumpf did not return a telephone call to his office Friday.
   Also mentioned was Ann Berman, a former deputy assistant
secretary of the Navy who now works for United Technologies. Berman
said she would have no comment.
   Paisley has not commented on the probe, but his attorney, E.
Lawrence Barcella, has criticized leaks of information about the
probe and has dismissed the allegations as ``garbage.''
   Of interest to investigators is Paisley's involvement _ both in
the Pentagon and as a consultant _ in the Advanced Tactical
Aircraft, one of the Navy's biggest procurement programs.
   McDonnell Douglas and General Dynamics are partners in the $4
billion program awarded last year to build the new aircraft.
   In another instance, the government searched for evidence that
Paisley supported Pratt & Whitney for the ``JVX project and V-22
engine,'' and ``payments or gratuities from Pratt and Whitney
employees to Paisley during his tenure as assistant secretary of
the Navy.''
   Paisley's involvement with foreign concerns also was targeted in
the search warrant. Investigators sought information about
Paisley's involvement with the Mazlat Co., an Israeli company.
   In 1986, the Navy awarded a $26 million contract to consortium
comprised of Mazlat and the American AAI corporation to build three
remotely piloted vehicles, known as drones.
   The FBI sought several items dealing with McDonnell Douglas, the
St. Louis-based defense contractor. The company supplies American
forces with helicopters and fighter planes, and is involved in
efforts to sell advanced fighter aircraft to several nations.
   An FBI list of items seized by agents at the Paisley's home
included tax returns, bank account numbers, Paisley's security
badge from General Dynamics and a ``confidential 12 pg memo re
visit to China.''
   Pentagon spokesman Fred S. Hoffman said the Defense Department
had no reaction to the revelations. ``We have it in hand and are
studying it,'' he said.
   Al Spivak, a spokesman for General Dynamics, said the company
``knows of no payment of bribes by this company or any of its
people'' to Paisley or his wife while Paisley was in the Navy or in
private life. James Linse, a spokesman for Pratt & Whitney, said he
could not comment because he had not seen the warrant.
</TEXT>
