<DOCNO> AP880709-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Airliner-Vincennes     07-09 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Vincennes,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Cruiser Had Radar Malfunction In June</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. missile cruiser that shot down
an Iranian passenger jet it mistook for a fighter plane was out of
action last month because its radar malfunctioned, U.S. officials
said.
   But a Navy spokesman said the breakdown on the USS Vincennes in
June was only a ``minor degradation'' and had no bearing on
Sunday's disaster that left 290 dead in the Persian Gulf.
   U.S. officials say the billion-dollar warship's high-tech radar
system received signals from the Iran Air Airbus A300 identifying
it as an Iranian F-14 fighter coming in for an attack. Iran said
all 290 people aboard were killed.
   The breakdown was reported on June 13 by The Associated Press,
although gulf-based U.S. Navy officials refused then to confirm
that the problem lay in the computerized system, called Aegis.
   The Aegis system of computer-linked radar and weapons is
designed primarily for defending a naval fleet in the open ocean
from air and missile attack. The Navy says it can detect, identify
and head off a threat developing hundreds of miles away.
   The 9,600-ton Vincennes arrived in the gulf May 27, the first of
the Navy's Aegis cruisers to be assigned to the U.S. naval force in
the waterway.
   It was assigned to patrol in the southern gulf, but by about
June 10 it was anchored off Bahrain, where Navy sources said it was
undergoing repair work on the radar system that lies at the core of
its capabilities.
   A Navy spokesman in the gulf, asked about the reported breakdown
at that time, said only that the ship was in port for ``maintenance
upkeep,'' the result of an unspecified problem.
   Officials here refused comment Friday, but a Navy spokesman at
the Pentagon, Lt. Brian Cullin, confirmed the Vincennes had been
down with a ``minor degradation'' of its radar system. He said
there was no connection between that and the shooting down of the
Iranian jetliner.
   ``The problem had absolutely no bearing on the whole incident,''
he said in a telephone interview. ``It (the cruiser) was never less
than 100 percent up on any mission capability, including
anti-aircraft warfare.''
   He said he could not confirm that the ship was out of action for
16 days, as reported by the Los Angeles Times.
   Cullin said the problem had actually been detected during the
Vincennes' 32-day voyage from San Diego to the Arabian Sea, where
it arrived May 22.
   A necessary replacement part was flown to the ship and installed
by the ship's own crew, he said, ``and the ship was back up on line
by June 6.''
   He said he did not know why the ship was then off the line
again, spending at least three days around June 10-13 at anchor
outside Bahrain, before it returned to its duty station in the
southern gulf.
   Some of the Vincennes' crew said they were puzzled why the ship
had been ordered to make a rush departure from San Diego after only
90 hours of port preparation, and on arrival spent five days in the
Gulf of Oman, ``sailing in circles'' as one officer described it,
before entering the Strait of Hormuz.
   Many Navy ships, especially those with sophisticated electronics
and other equipment, have civlian experts, known as ``tech reps,''
aboard to maintain and repair the gear. Most are employees of the
manufacturers.
   There were no such representatives aboard the Vincennes. Its
officers told journalists who rode the ship into the gulf that the
crew was fully capable of maintaining and repairing the ship's
complicated systems.
   The Vincennes was riding at anchor off Bahrain for a third day
Friday, but two other warships that contributed data to the
investigation of the jetliner incident, the frigate Elmer
Montgomery and the missile frigate John H. Sides, returned to duty
in the gulf.
   Both had been nearby when the aircraft was shot down. The
disaster followed a clash involving the Vincennes, the Elmer
Montgomery and some Iranian speedboats, two of which were sunk,
U.S. officials said.
   Computer tapes from the warships are being sent back to the
United States for analysis at the Navy's Surface warfare Center in
Dahlgren, Va. U.S. sources said they could offer no indication of
when a team of six military investigators sent here to investigate
the incident would complete their task and return to the United
States.
   The team, headed by Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty, arrived here
on Tuesday with orders to deliver a report in 15 days if possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
