<DOCNO> AP880709-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Pullout 1stLd-Writethru   07-09 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Pullout, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0444,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Premier Talks of Eventual Red Army Pullouts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with State Department comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov
says the Red Army will withdraw from foreign lands by the end of
the century, but a U.S. official says a Soviet pullout may be
imminent in Hungary.
   A State Department official said Friday that there are
``increasing indications'' of a unilateral withdrawal from Hungary,
which was invaded by Soviet troops in 1956 to crush an uprising.
   Reports of a possible Soviet withdrawal have circulated for a
year and a half. The State Department official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said its information is based on U.S.
intelligence reports.
   Ryzhkov, speaking to Western reporters Friday, gave no
indication that the Soviet union was preparing a unilateral
withdrawal from an East bloc nation before 2000.
   The Soviet government chief told Western reporters such moves
could come only in the context of a general withdrawal involving
Western forces as well.
   He said his government feels no armies should be on foreign
territory _ U.S., British or Soviet.
   ``Our proposal is this: let us take out all the armies,'' he
said. ``The armies in Czechoslovakia are part of the Warsaw Pact
armies. Let us agree on a radical solution in the West and in the
East.''
   Red Army units are stationed in several Soviet bloc countries,
including Czechoslovakia, Hungary and East Germany.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley cautioned that after
announcing troop withdrawals form East Germany in 1983, the Soviets
built their forces in that country back to the same levels within
three years.
   Currently, four Soviet tank and motorized rifle divisions remain
in Hungary. The troops are not on the front lines opposite NATO
forces, however, because Hungary is bordered to the west by three
Warsaw Pact nations and politically neutral Yugoslavia and Austria.
   Even with a withdrawal, said Oakley, the Warsaw Pact would hold
a 2-1 advantage over the North Atlantic Treaty Organization in
tanks, artillery and armored personnel vehicles.
   In talks with reporters, Ryzkhov also seemed to dash hopes for
any rehabilitation soon of Alexander Dubcek, the former Communist
Party leader in Czechoslovakia who is famed for his liberal
policies.
   Ryzhkov confirmed that at the recent Communist Party conference,
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev stressed the need for
``socialism with a human face.''
   That phrase was used to describe Dubcek's ``Prague spring'' of
1968, which provoked a Soviet-led Warsaw Pact invasion in August of
that year and cost Dubcek his job as party chief in Prague.
   Western reporters asked Ryzhkov, who attended a three-day
economic conference that ended Thursday, whether the time had not
come for Dubcek to be rehabilitated.
   He replied: ``The rehabilitation of Dubcek, that is a question
for Czechoslovakia. I do not intend to deal with the internal
problems of Czechoslovakia. As far as I know the Czechoslovak party
does not intend to deal with that.''
   Dubcek, now 66, said in an Austrian Television interview
broadcast Thursday that the current leadership in Prague should
adopt Gorbachev's reforms. Most are similar to reforms Dubcek
introduced here 20 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880709-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Obit-Clark     07-09 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Clark,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Space Reporter for Newsweek, New York Times Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evert Clark, who specialized in aviation,
science and space in 40 years of reporting for publications
including The New York Times and Newsweek, has died. He was 62.
   Clark, who was technical news editor for Business Week and other
magazines serviced by the McGraw-Hill World News Bureau for the
last 10 years, died Thursday at Montgomery General Hospital in
suburban Maryland after surgery for an aneurysm.
   Born in Gainesville, Ga., Clark began his career in journalism
in 1947 as a reporter and editor for the Durham, N.C., Morning
Herald.
   He became a feature writer for the Washington Daily News in 1948
before he turned his passion for aviation and space into a position
as the first space editor for Aviation Week and Space Technology
Magazine in 1956.
   He covered the U.S. effort to land a man on the moon and was
cited with an award by the National Space Club in 1969 for his
``penetrating, consistently informed and lucid writing.''
   He joined The New York Times in 1963 as an aviation and space
reporter in 1963 and moved to Newsweek in 1968, covering science
and technology as well as the Watergate break-in during his 10
years in the magazine's Washington bureau. He wrote a book titled
``Contrabandista'' with Newsweek colleague Nicholas Horrock on the
drug trade.
   Clark served in the Navy from 1944 to 1946 and graduated from
the University of North Carolina in 1947. He lived most recently in
Gaithersburg, Md.
   He is survived by his wife, June; one son, David S. Clark; and
two daughters, Kristin L. Dougherty and Amy S. Bockhaus.
