<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Airliner-Routes     07-09 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Routes,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airlines Seek To Avoid Military Confrontations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. downing of an Iranian jetliner has
prompted airlines flying over the Persian Gulf to seek ways to
avoid military confrontations.
   The issue topped the agenda when technical experts from six
major airlines operating passenger flights in the gulf area held a
regular meeting at the Geneva headquarters of the International Air
Transport Association.
   Thursday's session also was attended by an official of the
International Civil Aviation Organization, a U.N. agency that on
July 13 is to consider Iran's request for an investigation into the
tragedy.
   Association officials would not comment when asked about the
possibility of rerouting flights. They also declined to talk about
reported complaints of the U.S. Navy's contradicting plane
instructions from civilian air controllers.
   ``We reviewed procedures in the gulf area to see if the airlines
could help improve civil-military coordination,'' said Norman
Jackson, head of the group's technical department.
   ``We saw a number of areas where we could be helpful,'' he said
in a telephone interview. He declined to elaborate.
   Asked whether rerouting was discussed, he said: ``Any routing
changes through the gulf is a matter for ICAO _ the governments.''
   But the association, an industry association grouping most of
the world's airlines, seemed certain to be considering the idea,
too.
   ``We are in close touch with ICAO on technical aspects,''
Jackson said.
   Navy officials say they were unable to communicate with or
identify Iran Air flight 655 on Sunday before blasting it out of
the sky with a missile. All 290 people aboard were killed.
   The technical group did not discuss details of the incident
because it is still under investigation, Jackson said.
   ``We have no firm information to work with and see no point in
speculating,'' he said.
   Jackson declined to identify the airlines that took part in the
one-day meeting or the ICAO representative.
</TEXT>
