<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Obit-Phillips     07-09 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Phillips,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former CIA Operative Defended Agency In The 1970s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Atlee Phillips, 65, former chief of
Latin American and Caribbean operations for the Central
Intelligence Agency and later a vocal defender of the CIA, has died.
   Phillips, who died Thursday at his home, had suffered from
cancer.
   A native of Fort Worth, Texas, Phillips became a public defender
of the agency following his retirement from clandestine service in
1975. His actions came when the agency suffered criticism for a
number of abuses, including charges of domestic spying.
   He undertook the one-man public relations campaign after a
discussion with his 15-year-old daughter in which he revealed his
true occupation _ an undercover intelligence officer. ``But that's
dirty,'' was her response.
   A former actor who served as an Army Air Force gunner in World
War II, Phillips escaped from a German prisoner-of-war camp after
being shot down over Austria in 1944. After the war, Phillips
purchased an English language newspaper in Chile, where he was
recruited by the agency.
   During his quarter of a century with the CIA, Phillips served as
station chief in Venezuela, Brazil and the Dominican Republic; he
operated a radio station on an island off the coast of Cuba in the
early months of Fidel Castro's rule, and did undercover duty in
Guatemala, Mexico City and Beirut.
   Phillips was founder and president of the Association of Foreign
Intelligence Officers, a frequent speaker of the college lecture
circuit, and the author of ``The Nightwatch: 25 Years of Peculiar
Service.''
   He is survived by his wife, Virginia Phillips, of Bethesda, Md.,
four children and three stepchildren.
</TEXT>
