<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     07-09 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises To 115, Reports Say 5 Million Marooned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrential rains swelled rivers and
sparked flooding that crushed homes and capsized boats, marooning
millions of people and killing up to 115, authorities said.
   The Water Development Board warned that the flooding that has
plagued the country for the past week could worsen in the next two
days.
   The board said in a statement issued Friday that all rivers in
the Brahmaputra basin were rising from the rain and the onrush of
waters from northeastern Indian states.
   The army was called out Friday to assist with rescue opertions.
Press reports said as many as 5 million people were marooned in
northeastern districts.
   ``The number of marooned people is so huge you cannot bring all
of them to safer places,'' said an official in the town of
Sunamganj, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Sunamganj is 112 miles northeast of the capital at Dhaka.
   Vice President Nurul Islam flew to the Sunamganj area by
helicopter Friday to assess flood damage. The aircraft was unable
to land because no suitable dry ground could be found, an aide said
today on condition of anonymity.
   Twenty-four more deaths occurred Friday, according to local
government officials and newspaper reports, raising the unofficial
death toll to at least 115.
   The government confirmed 10 new deaths and said its official
count stood at 60.
   The New Nation, an independent English-language daily, and
Ittefaq, a Bengali-language daily, blamed the deaths on houses
collapsing and boats capsizing.
   Most of the deaths were reported in the northeast, which has
been hardest hit by the floods.
   Bangladesh, one of the poorest nations in the world with a
population of more than 105 million, often suffers flooding during
the annual monsoon rain season.
   Its low-lying land is vulnerable because not enough dams have
been constructed on major rivers to control water flow.
   Press reports said rescue efforts were hampered by relentless
rain.
   Thousands of people were trapped on rooftops or high ground
without food, press reports said. The Ittefaq newspaper said there
were reports of outbreaks of diarrhea and other water-borne
diseases because of a shortage of pure drinking water.
   The northeastern tea-growing district of Sylhet was all but cut
off from the rest of the country Friday when the main highway
bridge washed away. Air service to the region was suspended earlier
in the week when runways flooded.
   In Hobiganj, just southwest of Sylhet, a tributary of the
Brahmaputra River was flowing more than 5 feet above flood level,
the highest in memory, the Water Development Board said.
   In Moulvibazar in the district just south of Sylhet, town
leaders urged residents to leave for higher ground as the town's
protective embankment threatened to cave in, officials there said.
</TEXT>
