<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     07-09 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assembly Passes Laws To Subpoena Ex-President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly today passed two
laws that could force former President Chun Doo-hwan to testify on
charges of corruption that allegedly occurred during his seven-year
tenure.
   Government party officials said they would ask President Roh
Tae-woo to veto the laws approved by the opposition-controlled
legislature. The proposals were passed 164-125, with three
absentions.
   If vetoed, the bills likely would die because the opposition
lacks the two-thirds legislative majority needed to override a
presidential veto. South Korea's three predominant opposition
parties together control 166 seats in the 299-member National
Assembly.
   The governing Democratic Justice Party criticized the proposals
and said Roh would certainly veto them. Party officials argued the
bills are unconstitutional.
   ``It is highly regrettable that the opposition rammed the law
bills through the Assembly in disregard of our repeated warnings
that they would be vetoed,'' Democratic Justice Party floor leader
Kim Yoon-hwan said.
   Kim Won-ki, floor leader for the Party for Peace and Democracy,
the largest opposition group, said he doubted Roh would veto the
bills.
   ``I don't think President Roh would veto the bills. He has
repeatedly promised that there would be no sanctuary in
investigating past corruption and irregularities,'' the opposition
leader said.
   The legislation contains a provision that empowers the National
Assembly to subpoena witnesses with writs of arraignment issued by
courts of law.
   Opposition politicians said such a law is needed to compel all
witnesses to testify in South Korea's huge government corruption
case.
   They said privately that the main targets of the laws are Chun
and his family.
   Roh and other top government officials maintain that they would
support efforts to ferret out all past corruption and
irregularities under Chun but the president oppose any moves to
make the Chun testify or stand trial.
   Chun, whose term ended in February, has come under public fire
for alleged involvement in large-scale financial scandals. One of
his brothers, Chun Kyung-hwan, was arrested in March for embezzling
millions of dollars.
   Several parliamentary committees were organized this week to
look into alleged corruption and other problems under Chun.
   One committee is charged with probing a 1980 anti-government
uprising in the southern city of Kwangju that left nearly 200 dead
and more than 800 others injured, according to official count.
   Opposition and dissident groups allege that Chun, along with Roh
and the United States, helped mastermind the brutal suppression of
the uprising.
</TEXT>
