<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cambodia     07-09 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thailand Calls For International Pressure To Prevent Return of
Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand's foreign minister said today
that an international peacekeeping force could prevent the Khmer
Rouge from retaking power in Cambodia after Vietnamese occupation
forces leave.
   Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila said Thailand and its
Southeast Asian allies do not want to see a return of the Khmer
Rouge, who killed up to 3 million people when they ruled Cambodia
from 1975 until the Vietnamese invasion of 1978.
   Previously, officials of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations, which strongly backs a three-party resistance coalition
that includes the Khmer Rouge, did not issue a strong public stand
on the issue.
   Siddhi spoke at a news conference ending a three-day annual
conference of foreign ministers of ASEAN.
   ``I think the Khmer Rouge know that they cannot come back
because we don't support them to come back,'' he said. ``So I think
we can use a lot of pressure besides the peacekeeping force.
   ``They know that ASEAN ... is trying to support a resolution of
the Cambodian problem by not supporting the return of the Khmer
Rouge,'' he said.
   At the same news conference, Secretary of State George Shultz
said that during his upcoming visit to China, he plans to stress
America's opposition to the Khmer Rouge. China is the Khmer Rouge's
main source of arms.
   ``The Chinese attitude toward the Khmer Rouge and the nature of
the continuing support to an overall Cambodian settlement will be a
very important factor, and recent statements by China are
encouraging in that regard,'' Shultz said.
   Also important to a political settlement, Shultz said, is the
Soviet Union's influence on Vietnam. He said the Kremlin gives
Vietnam $2 billion in military aid a year.
   The Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia from 1975 until the Vietnamese
invasion in December 1978. During that time, they killed millions
of Cambodians. The group is known for its radical agrarian
communism.
   Shultz reiterated U.S. support for a central role in any
settlement for Prince Norodom Sihanouk, a former Cambodian head of
state who now leads the guerrilla coalition. The third group in the
resistance is led by Son Sann, a Western-leaning politician.
   Shultz said he hoped the Cambodian peace talks planned for
Indonesia on July 25 would be successful. The talks are to involve
the guerrilla groups, the Vietnamese-installed government in
Cambodia, Vietnam, Laos and the ASEAN countries.
   Vietnam has said it will pull its estimated 140,000 troops out
of Cambodia by 1990 and has begun withdrawing 50,000 troops in an
operation to be completed in December.
   Delegates said ASEAN ministers did not discuss the Khmer Rouge
issue during their conference on Monday and Tuesday. Bit it became
a dominant topic when the Western dialogue partners joined in
consultations starting Thursday.
   ASEAN groups Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore, Indonesia, the
Philippines and Brunei. Its dialogue partners are the United
States, Japan, Australia, Canada, New Zealand and the European
Community.
</TEXT>
