<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0514EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan     07-09 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Personnel Shift Indicates Partial Change Of Leadership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Nationalist Party indicated
today that several, but not all, of the island's old-guard leaders
are to retire.
   Ten of the 31 members of the Nationalist's policy-making Central
Standing Committee were named to the Central Advisory Committee,
which is composed primarily of retired officials.
   Nationalist Party spokesman Raymond Tai told reporters that
advisory panel members will not sit on the new Central Standing
Committee to be named Thursday at the end of the weeklong 13th
party congress.
   The average age of current Central Standing Committee members is
70, with seven members more than 80 years old. More than half fled
to Taiwan with Chiang Kai-shek from the Chinese mainland when his
Nationalist government was routed by the Communists in 1949.
   Leaders of the Nationalist Party, also known as the Kuomintang,
have stressed the importance of promoting younger party members who
represent the Taiwan public.
   Young party members have criticized old-guard conservatives from
the mainland for not being enthusiastic about the liberalization
policies initiated by President Chiang Ching-kuo before his death
in January.
   Chiang, the eldest son of Chiang Kai-shek, lifted martial law,
allowed new political parties and eased a ban on travel to mainland
China.
   Still to be changed is the parliamentary system in which
mainland Chinese Nationalists hold a majority of seats to back the
party's claim that it remains the rightful ruler of China.
   President Lee Teng-hui, who was acclaimed the first native
Taiwanese party chairman Friday, has vowed to continue the process
of democratic change and liberalization but has moved cautiously in
past months as he has sought to consolidate power.
   The new members of the advisory committee, proposed by Lee and
approved by the congress, include five of seven octagenarians on
the Central Standing Committee.
   Three media executives on the Central Standing Committee who
have said they want to give way to a younger leadership also were
named to the advisory panel.
   But Premier Yu Kuo-hwa and Shen Chang-huan, secretary to the
president, were not named to the advisory group. The two
74-year-olds are influential conservatives and liberals fear they
could block reforms.
   ``This will be a very conservative restructuring,'' said
political journalist Antonio Chiang. But he added that the
conservative old-guard's power base was dwindling and younger
members would likely be more willing to speak up.
   The 1,209 congress delegates will elect a 180-member Central
Committee on Tuesday. For the first time, the vote will not be
limited to candidates proposed by the party.
   The new Central Committee will meet Thursday to name the new
Central Standing Committee. A Cabinet overhaul is expected later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
