<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Councils     07-09 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Councils,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Regional Black Councils</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has proposed
the creation of regional legislative councils to address matters
related solely to blacks. Anti-apartheid activists condemned the
proposal.
   Blacks would elect members to the regional councils under the
proposed Extension of Political Participation Bill, which was
published Friday in the official Government Gazette.
   The bill did not specify how many councils would be established.
President P.W. Botha would have the power to veto bills passed by
the councils.
   Presently, blacks can vote only in municipal elections and in 10
homelands. Elected black officials are widely viewed in their
communities as collaborators with the white-led government.
   South Africa's 26 million blacks have no representation in
Parliament and cannot vote in national elections. Its 5 million
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools
and health services.
   The proposed councils would have authority over regional matters
concerning blacks such as education, welfare, local government and
community development.
   ``It is the government's viewpoint that all communities should
participate in the government process on the different levels,''
said Chris Heunis, minister of constitutional development and
planning.
   Helen Suzman, member of Parliament for the Progressive Federal
Party, said the proposal was ``one of those hopeless efforts to
avoid the realities of the South African situation.''
   ``The duplication of (government) structures to run this country
has become totally absurd,'' she said.
   Anti-apartheid activists have rejected all the government's
major political reform proposals in recent years, saying they
entrench white domination and continue to divide political
participation by race.
   The government is seeking comment on the latest proposal before
deciding whether it will be introduced in Parliament, Heunis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
