<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Malaysia-Judges 1stLd-Writethru   07-09 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Malaysia-Judges, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0477,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bar Council Calls On Chief Justice To Resign</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with three grafs to CORRECT title of highest ranking
judge. Pick up 4th pvs, `Salleh had...' ADDS 1 graf of background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Malaysian Bar Council today
urged acting Lord President Justice Abdul Hamid Omar, the country's
highest ranking judge, to resign and said it would begin contempt
of court proceedings against him.
   The unprecedented action by the Bar Council, which represents
2,500 lawyers in Malaysia, was the latest move in a battle between
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and the judiciary, the only branch
of government still independent of his control.
   The battle began May 26 when the government suspended the
previous Lord President, Mohamad Salleh Abas, and accused him of
``lack of dignity, judicial propriety and impartiality.''
   Salleh had written to King Sultan Mahmood Iskandar and
complained that Mahathir had been attacking the judiciary.
   Last Saturday, five Supreme Court judges ordered a tribunal
hearing the charges against Salleh not to advise the king on
whether to remove Salleh permanently until it received further
orders.
   On Wednesday, the king suspended the five judges and ordered
them to face a tribunal that will decide whether they will be
removed permanently.
   He acted on a request from Hamid, who alleged that the five were
guilty of misbehavior.
   ``By his recent actions ... Hamid Omar has shown himself as
unfit for judicial office,'' the council said.
   ``The Malaysian Bar calls for immediate revocation of the
suspension of the five judges of the Supreme Court, as the
suspensions are totally inconsistent with the independence of the
judiciary and will lead to the destruction of the judiciary as an
independent branch of government,'' the council said.
   Deputy Prime Minister Abdul Ghafar Baba denied on Friday that
politicians were undermining the independence of the judiciary.
   In February, the high court ruled that Mahathir's party, the
United Malays National Organization, was illegal because it had
branches that were not registered with the authorities as required
by law. Since then, Mahathir has set up a new party called ``New
UMNO'' and has been busy recruiting old members.
</TEXT>
