<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     07-09 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Drench Midwest; Heat Bakes East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain drenched parts of the Midwest today while triple-digit,
record-setting temperatures were forecast for many Eastern states
in a continuing heat wave that contributed to the death of a
Pennsylvania infant.
   Much of the central Plains reported heavy rains Friday night and
early today from thunderstorms extending across western Kansas,
much of Nebraska and northwest Iowa.
   Severe thunderstorm activity diminished early Friday evening
after touching off almost a dozen tornadoes over northeast
Colorado. No major damage was reported.
   In Indiana, Pa., a 3{-month-old girl died Thursday of
dehydration and exposure to extreme heat after her mother
apparently left her in a closed car for four hours. At Pittsburgh
International Airport, about 30 miles to the west, Friday's high of
99 broke the record of 97 set in 1876.
   West Virginia broiled under a second straight day of 100-degree
heat Friday. Triple-digit record highs were reported in Charleston
and Huntington.
   In Indiana, the South Bend high of 97 on Friday broke the record
of 96 set in 1985. Other Indiana cities sweltered under even hotter
conditions, including 102 at Evansville; 101 at Fort Wayne,
Indianapolis and Lafayette; and 100 at Terre Haute.
   In Illinois, the state issued an ozone advisory for parts of
Madison and St. Clair counties and some adjacent territory Friday
after levels of the pollutant reached up to 127 parts per billion.
A level of 120 parts per billion is considered ``unhealthful,''
said an agency spokesman.
   Ozone is created when heat and the sun react with other
pollutants such as hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides.
   In New Hampshire, state officials said brook trout and other
fish were dying as water temperatures in southern streams and
rivers rose to more than 80 degrees.
   ``They're cold-water animals and they die of heat stroke,'' said
Sgt. Ronald Evans, a Fish and Game Department district manager.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from northern Michigan across the upper Mississippi Valley, the
central and southern Plains and the central and southern Rockies to
portions of Arizona; and showers and thunderstorms over the lower
Mississippi Valley, central and southern Florida and the northern
Atlantic Coast states.
   Most of the nation was forecast to have high temperatures
between 85 and 95 degrees; record temperatures of around 100
degrees were forecast through the Tennessee and Ohio valleys,
across Indiana and Ohio and over portions of the East Coast; in the
lower 80s over northern Minnesota and across the western Great
Plains; the upper 60s and 70s along the Pacific Coast; over 100
through interior valleys of California; and near 110 in the desert
Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49 at
Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 98 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 78 fair; Boston 75 hazy; Buffalo 77 hazy;
Charleston, S.C. 74 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 83 hazy; Cleveland 72
hazy; Detroit 75 fair; New York 68 fair; Philadelphia 77 cloudy;
Pittsburgh 74 hazy; Portland, Maine 77 hazy; Washington 77 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 64 fair; Chicago 79 hazy; Dallas-Fort Worth
74 fair; Denver 62 fair; Des Moines 72 fair; Indianapolis 75 hazy;
Kansas City 75 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 72 partly cloudy;
Nashville 83 fair; New Orleans 76 partly cloudy; St. Louis 78 hazy.
   _West: Albuquerque 65 partly cloudy; Anchorage 58 fair; Las
Vegas 86 fair; Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 98 fair; Salt Lake City
72 fair; San Diego 65 fair; San Francisco 53 fair; Seattle 65 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 77 partly cloudy; Toronto 70 fair.
</TEXT>
