<DOCNO> AP880709-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Women     07-09 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Women,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Drafts Regulations To Protect Women Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has drafted comprehensive rules
for women workers, barring them from hard physical labor and
lengthening their maternity leaves, a report said today.
   The regulations also ban discrimination against women, but only
if the work is deemed ``suitable for women workers,'' according to
the official China Daily.
   It said the regulations stipulate the kind and intensity of work
suitable to women and bar them from labor-intensive jobs such as
mining and leather-making. The criteria used in determining what
jobs were suitable was not given.
   The regulations were drafted by the ministries of labor and
public health, the All-China Trade Union and the All-China Women's
Federation, and have been approved in principle by the State
Council, the top executive body, the report said.
   The rules guarantee women the right to refuse job assignments
that could harm their health; allow one year of maternity leave
with 90 paid days, up from the current 56; and guarantee rest
periods for pregnant and menstruating women and those who have just
had abortions.
   The newspaper did not comment on the possibility that the
regulations would discourage employers from hiring women, who
according to official reports already face greater difficulty than
men in finding urban jobs.
   In the countryside most women do farmwork, although growing
numbers of male peasants are leaving the land to work in small
factories.
   The traditional belief that women are inferior to men is still
deeply ingrained in Chinese society. The Guangming Daily reported
last year that dozens of women graduates of People's University in
Beijing were rejected by the work units to which the state had
assigned them. Some units said they did not employ women.
   Now that factory managers have been given the power to fire
workers in recent years, women have been dismissed in larger
numbers than men, official reports have said.
   The China Daily said the new regulations ``contain clear
stipulations that all working units suitable for women workers
should not reject female job applicants on any pretext.''
   It did not say what sanctions, if any, would be applied against
employers found guilty of discrimination.
   Chinese law already bars women from working in mines, but
thousands are estimated to do so because mining often is the
best-paid work in rural areas.
   Despite the egalitarian ideology of Mao Tse-tung and the
equality still promised in the Constitution, women have always been
treated as second-class citizens in China.
   During Mao's rule, when government and party committees on
various levels were handpicked, one or two women would be put on
them. Now there is limited choice in elections for such committees,
and women are getting voted out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
