<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-IranAirliner     07-09 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Iran Airliner,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze: Airliner Shootdown A Consequence of U.S. Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
said today that the U.S. downing of an Iranian airliner in the
Persian Gulf was dramatic proof of what an American policy of
building up tensions can lead to.
   It was the highest-level official Soviet comment to date on
Sunday's disaster, in which the cruiser USS Vincennes shot down an
Iran Air Airbus.
   The United States said he crew mistook the plane for an F-14
fighter. Iran said all 290 people aboard were killed.
   Shevardnadze met in Moscow with U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock at
Matlock's request to discuss various regional issues, the Tass news
agency said. It provided a brief report on the meeting.
   Commenting on the airliner's destruction, Shevardnadze said,
``This was not an accident, but dramatic evidence showing what a
policy from positions of strength and of building up tensions can
lead to.''
   Shevaradnadze also repeated the Kremlin's demand that all
foreign warships withdraw from the Persian Gulf. The Soviets
contend such a concentration of military might increases the danger
of conflict.
   Since the airliner's destruction, Soviet officials have issued
relatively mild criticism of the United States, apparently because
of reluctance to cause any chill in improved superpower relations.
State-run media have carried much tougher remarks, including
accusations that the U.S. Navy warship committed ``deliberate mass
murder in cold blood.''
   Shevardnadze, a member of the 13-man ruling Politburo, was the
highest-level Kremlin official to comment publicly on the Iranian
airliner disaster.
   Tass said the Soviet foreign minister and Matlock also discussed
the Nicaraguan conflict and that Shevardnadze criticized ``the
anti-Nicaraguan policy of the U.S.''
   Shevardnadze said the Soviets firmly intend to keep providing
aid to Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government, which is fighting
U.S.-backed Contra rebels.
   He said Nicaragua's government ``is fighting for the
independence and sovereignty of its country, for the right of its
people to have a free choice,'' Tass reported.
</TEXT>
