<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-ForestFires     07-09 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Forest Fires,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Die in Fires on Western Ionian Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people, including three Britons, died
in raging forest fires on the western resort islands of Cephalonia
and Corfu, police said today.
   The officials said Irene Evans, a 32-year-old mother of three,
died from burns on Friday while being airlifted by helicopter to a
hospital in the town of Argostoli in Cephalonia.
   Two of Evans' daughters, Jenny, 10, and Maria, 3, also died in
the fire that broke out early Friday near the village of Lakithra
on the Ionian island.
   The officials, who declined to be identified in accordance with
Greek practice, said 14-year-old Angela Evans survived the flames
but was listed in critical condition in an Athens hospital.
   They said five other Greeks were also hospitalized with burns.
   A police spokesman on Cephalonia said Evans, of Greek origin,
had been vacationing on the island without her husband, Tom. He
said the Evans family lived in London.
   The spokesman said two hotels on the island were evacuated and
some tourists spent the night on a beach.
   A Greek woman, Eleni Konstantatou, 82, also died in the fire on
Cephalonia, according to the officials.
   The officials said George Efthimiades, 60, died while battling
the flames with teams of firefighters on Corfu.
   High winds gusting up to 25 miles were hampering firefighters'
efforts to put out the blazes on both resort islands, forestry
officials said.
   Another fire was raging out of control through the forests of
Mount Olympus, home of the legendary Greek gods in northern Greece,
Alekos Voutsaras, a forestry official at the agriculture ministry
said.
   ``We've got hundreds of firefighters, soldiers and nine
firefighting planes battling all three blazes but the strong winds
are really hampering us,'' Voutsaras told The Associated Press.
   The forestry official said it still wasn't clear how any of the
three fires started or how much damage they had caused.
   The blazes on both islands broke out on the seventh day of a
heat wave that has sent temperatures soaring past 104 degrees
Fahrenheit range and has left more than 30 dead.
   More than 3,000 people have been admitted to hospitals because
of the blistering temperatures.
</TEXT>
