<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   07-09 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0463,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Braces for Losses, Demands Recount; Opposition
Outraged</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with detail of recount request,
Cardenas' comments; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition candidate in Mexico's
presidential elections said today the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party was seeking to steal victory with its demand
for a recount of votes in the capital.
   National Democratic Front candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas told a
news conference that the governing party had petitioned the Federal
Elections Commission to nullify voting in the Federal District
because thousands of voters had used differing party symbols to
cast ballots for Cardenas.
   Cardenas is listed on the ballots as the presidential candidate
of three different parties. Those parties subsequently merged as
the National Democratic Front to back his candidacy.
   The Commission had rejected a Democratic Front request before
the election that ballots be reprinted to list Cardenas only once.
   The governing party's recount request is ``absurd,'' Cardenas
said. ``Our information shows we have won in nearly all, if not
all, 40 districts of the Federal District.
   ``I call upon the president of the Republic (and governing
party) candidate Carlos Salinas de Gortari to comply with their
word and their commitment to preserve the legality of this
electoral process,'' he said.
   Early and partial returns released by the Federal Electoral
Commission on Friday showed Salinas with 47.4 percent of the 4.5
million votes tabulated. The commission said Cardenas had 26.7
percent of the vote and Manuel J. Clouthier of the conservative
National Action Party had 20.7 percent.
   Final results for the presidential election and for the 64-seat
Senate and 500-seat Congress are to be released Sunday.
   The governing party has won every presidential election since it
was created in 1929, but this year's presidential and congressional
balloting was expected to be the closest in years.
   The Commission did not say how many of Mexico's 38 million
registered voters actually cast ballots on Wednesday.
   The governing party's chairman, Jorge de la Vega Dominguez,
earlier had proclaimed victory in at least 27 of Mexico's 31 states
and said opposition accusations of fraud were meant to confuse the
electorate.
   Porfirio Munoz Ledo, a Front Senate candidate and former
chairman of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, charged that the
governing party was printing extra ballots to replace those it was
seeking to annul. The new ballots would be marked with
Institutional Revolutionary Party votes, he said.
   ``Just Friday morning everyone in the government knew we had
won'' the Mexico City race, Munoz Ledo said. ``Now they are
de-legitimizing everything.''
   Munoz Ledo also indicated the Front was leading in the states of
Michoacan, Mexico, Morelos and Guerrero.
   On Friday, Salinas appeared to be preparing supporters for the
party's first federal losses since it was founded in 1929.
   ``The results so far ratify this circumstance of plurality ...
and a new political reality in Mexico,'' Salinas said.
   Cardenas said today the election commission had promised not to
release any returns until the vote count was completed and charged
the figures included results from voting stations where the
Institutional Revolutionary Party said it won 100 percent of the
votes or did not permit opposition poll-watchers to be present.
   ``The Interior Secretary broke the commitments he gave'' not to
publish incomplete results and ``released these data without
consulting the various parties,'' Cardenas said.
   Institutional Revolutionary Party officials, speaking on
condition of anonymity, had said Friday the governing party may
have to concede that Cardenas won in Michoacan, Morelos and the
capital. They said Cardenas might also win in the state of Mexico,
which abuts the federal district on three sides.
   Salinas said the opposition's presence will be most felt in the
Chamber of Deputies, where a two-thirds majority is necessary to
pass legislation. The chamber traditionally has been little more
than a rubber stamp for the Institutional Revolutionary Party.
   ``There we're going to see intensely this new reality,'' Salinas
said.
   Earlier Friday, Clouthier accused the government of delaying an
election announcement ``to see how to disguise the figures.'' He
called a rally for today in Mexico City's central square, where his
party planned to release its own vote count.
   Hundreds of National Action Party supporters celebrated Friday
in Ciudad Juarez to mark what they believed was a victory there. A
party motorcade crisscrossed the city in triumph, but all was quiet
at the city's Institutional Revolutionary Party offices.
   The Assembly for Effective Suffrage, a watchdog group, said it
discovered 1,100 cases of irregularities ranging from
ballot-stuffing and tampering with voter registration rolls.
   Alfonso Bravo, president of Justice and Peace, one of the
organizations comprising the assembly, said the group had detected
voting irregularities in 20 percent of the approximately 28,000
voting booths it had monitored.
</TEXT>
