<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OfficerKilled     07-09 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Officer Killed,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Killed In Shootout; Officer Wounds Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Maryland prison escapees face
first-degree murder charges in the slaying of a police officer who
was shot to death after he stopped the vehicle they were riding in.
   Officer Ernest Ponce De Leon, 40, was the first full-time
officer killed in the police department's 143-year history. Four
people in the car, including the escapees, were wounded in a gun
battle Friday with another officer who came to the scene to assist
Ponce De Leon.
   Ponce De Leon died minutes after he was shot twice in the chest,
said police spokesman Phil Kiracofe. A former reserve officer and
probation official, Ponce De Leon became a full-time officer in
1986.
   The four injured people were arrested after the shooting behind
a laundry several miles southwest of downtown.
   Police say Clarence J. Jones, 33, went to the trunk of the
vehicle supposedly to retrieve identification but pulled a pistol
and opened fire, said Kiracofe.
   The three escapees were wounded by Officer Greg Armstrong, a
member of the department for less than a year. The fourth person in
the car, a Jacksonville woman, was probably hit by gunfire from one
of the escapees, Kiracfe said.
   Armstrong ``emptied his weapon at least once and had to reload
under an awful lot of pressure. He fired a lot of rounds,'' said
Kiracofe. Armstrong was armed with a .357-caliber Magnum service
revolver.
   The escapees were identified as Jones, who was serving 25 years
for robbery with a deadly weapon and attempted robbery; Henry
Goins, 26, who was serving 12 years for rape, kidnapping and
robbery with a deadly weapon; and Irvin Griffin, 28, who was
serving 45 years for assault with intent to murder.
   Jones was treated for a gunshot to the face and turned over to
police for questioning, said Kiracofe. Goins was in critical
condition with a gunshot wound to the head, said Ron Brafford,
spokesman for Tallahassee Memorial Regional Medical Center. Griffin
was listed in stable condition with a gunshot to the thigh at
Tallahassee Memorial.
   They were charged with first-degreee murder Friday night, and
under the state's felony murder rule could be given a death
sentence if convicted.
   The fourth occupant, Beverly Lee Harris, 39, a longtime
acquaintance of Griffin, was reported in stable condition at
Tallahassee Community Hospital by Ronald Rudderman, assistant
hospital administrator.
   The whereabouts of the fourth Maryland escapee, Douglas
Edgerton, 21, who was serving a 20-year sentence for second-degree
murder, were unknown.
   The four escaped June 25 by overpowering a guard at the Maryland
House of Correction.
   In Tallahassee, it was the department's first death of an
officer in the line of duty since 1982 when a reserve motorcycle
officer was killed in an accident while escorting astronaut John
Young. Until then, no Tallahassee officer had been killed in the
line of duty, said Kiracofe.
</TEXT>
