<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShivaeeVerdict     07-09 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shivaee Verdict,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Iranian Miliary Pilot Convicted of Killing Doctor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Iranian Air Force pilot was
convicted early today in the shooting death of a doctor, also a
native of Iran, in what the family of the dead man called a
political assassination.
   The Berkeley County Circuit Court jury recommended mercy at the
sentencing of Mozaffer Shivaee, 30, of Escondido, Calif.
   Shivaee was convicted in the slaying of Dr. Morteza Fard, 50.
Fard was killed at a city park in this eastern West Virginia city
on July 3, 1987.
   Shivaee could be sentenced to life in prison. No sentencing date
has been set, pending the filing of post-verdict motions, officials
said.
   Psychologist Leroy Stone, testifying for the defense, said
Shivaee may have had ``delusions'' of an affair between his wife
and the physician. Stone said he was unable to find any evidence
that an affair actually took place.
   Shivaee worked for Fard in his Tehran clinic from 1978 to 1982.
Fard also lived in California for a time after leaving Iran in 1982.
   After the shooting, Fard family members said the two men had
been on opposite political sides in Iran and they contended that
the shooting was a political assassination.
   When arrested minutes after the shooting, carrying a .38-caliber
handgun, Shivaee told the arresting officer that he was on ``a
mission.''
   The day of the shooting, a Washington television said it
received a telephone call indicating that the doctor was
assassinated because of his political views.
   Fard was a staff physician at City Hospital in Martinsburg and
was an expert on nerve and muscle therapy.
</TEXT>
