<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan     07-09 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Envoy Calls For Sept. 1 Cease-Fire in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. official today called for a
Sept. 1 cease-fire in Afghanistan and establishment of an interim
Afghan government that would exclude guerrillas or officials under
Marxist President Najib.
   U.N. envoy Diego Cordovez, making his comments a a news
conference after returning from the Afghan capital of Kabul, said
the proposed government would consist of ``recognized independent
and impartial'' Afghans.
   Cordovez said the new government would be effective Sept. 1,
when a cease-fire would go into effect, and that it would convene a
grand council of leaders no later than March 1.
   The grand council is a traditional Afghan decision-making body
whose leaders were chosen according to the country's tribal
structure.
   Cordovez said he believes such a council would be able to
establish a government with broad-based support, while Najib's
national reconciliation plan and attempts by supporters of the
guerrillas to generate mass support have failed.
   The guerrillas did not immediately comment on Cordovez' peace
plan, but a spokesman for a moderate guerrilla group opposed any
negotiations with the communist Afghan government.
   ``We will not have anything to do with communists, any kind of
communists,'' said Azim Nasser-Zia, of the National Islamic Front
of Afghanistan.
   He also called for a ``cooling-off'' period in the fighting
before Sept. 1, during which the interim government would be
chosen. Afghan guerrilla leaders, backed by China, Pakistan and the
United States, have insisted that they will continue to fight until
Soviet troops are out of Afghanistan and the Kabul government is
toppled.
   ``I doubt whether there could be a cooling-off period,'' said
Ikram Gran, spokesman for the seven-party Afghan Alliance, which
has its headquarters in Pakistan's northwestern city of Peshawar.
   Gran said, however, that he and Nasser-Zia both supported the
selection of the ``independent and impartial'' representatives.
They suggested the new leaders could be chosen among former Cabinet
ministers and officials now living in exile.
   Cordovez returned to Islamabad Friday from Kabul, where he met
with Najib, other Afghan leaders and Soviet Gen. Valentin Verenikov.
   Cordovez negotiated the April 14 Geneva accords which provide
for the phased withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   The Kremlin sent troops and tanks into Afghanistan in December
1979 to back the Communist government. In the April pact, the
Soviets agreed to pull out the more than 100,000 troops they
deployed.
   Half of the troops are to be out of the country by Aug. 15 and
the remainder by Feb. 15.
   Cordovez said 32,000 Soviet troops have already left
Afghanistan. He said Soviet military representatives assured him
the withdrawal was proceeding as planned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
