<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     07-09 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Vow Revenge For Death Squad Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels on Saturday blamed
President Corazon Aquino for the upsurge in attacks by right-wing
deaths squads on leftists and human rights activists, and they
pledged reprisals.
   Government troops killed at least 15 rebels in separate clashes
on the main island of Luzon and on southern Mindanao island, the
military said.
   ``The Aquino government and its U.S. backers cannot escape their
full responsibility for the crimes committed by forces of state
terrorism against the people,'' the National Democratic Front said
in a statement sent to news agencies.
   ``At the same time, unofficial death squads have killed a
mounting number of prominent individuals who had courageously made
common cause with their suffering countrymen.'' it said.
   The Front, the political wing of the outlawed Communist Party of
the Philippines, said it is futile for victims of right-wing
extremists to expect justice from Mrs. Aquino's government. It
urged them to support the 19-year-old communist insurgency instead.
   On July 2, gunmen believed to be right-wing extremists
assassinated human rights lawyer Emmanuel Mendoza in Manila.
Mendoza was the third human rights lawyer to be killed in two weeks
in the Philippines.
   On June 30, Nemesio Prudente, a leftist university president,
was seriously wounded in an ambush. The ambush, the second on
Prudente in seven months, left three of his security aides dead and
five others wounded.
   Police have arrested five Manila policemen and an anti-communist
vigilante in connection with Prudente's second attack.
   ``By its declared total war policy and refusal to heed popular
clamor against state-sponsored terrorism, the U.S.-Aquino regime is
called to account for these crimes,'' the Front said.
   The rebels pledged ``that revolutionary justice will be done _
fascist criminals will be punished, the people will be defended _
firmly and judiciously.''
   In Quezon province, government troops backed by artillery fire
and four helicopter gunships have killed at least 10 communist
rebels since Friday in a bid to rescue five officers held captive
by the guerrillas, Col. Hernani Figueroa said Saturday.
   Figueroa, spokesman for the Southern Luzon Command, said the
clash occured on the outskirts of Tayabas town in Quezon province,
about 55 miles south of Manila.
   Soldiers were pursuing rebels believed to be holding five
military officers they captured June 1 at a guerrilla checkpoint in
a nearby town, he said.
   In Davao del Sur province, soldiers killed five rebels Friday in
a battle on the outskirts of Davao city, 600 miles south of Manila,
Lt. Col. Franco Calida said. He said 15 rebels were wounded but
were able to escape.
   In Pangasinan province, the military reported that it uncovered
two mass graves Friday with 20 bodies in the village of San Macario
Sur, about 100 miles north of Manila. The victims were believed to
have been executed by communist rebels.
   At least 65 soldiers, policemen and civilian informers have been
killed in Manila this year in attacks blamed on the rebels, police
say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
