<DOCNO> AP880709-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-AirportSit-In     07-09 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Airport Sit-In,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wife of Exiled Burundian President Stages Airport Sit-In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of the deposed president of
Burundi sat in the VIP lounge of Nairobi's international airport
for the fifth straight day Saturday after being barred from
traveling to Burundi to see her children.
   The Burundi government, in a statement issued in Nairobi,
claimed former leader Jean-Paul Bagaza was orchestrating the
protest from Uganda. He has lived there intermittently since being
ousted in a bloodless coup Sept. 3.
   Bagaza's wife, Faust, has been living in the lounge at Nairobi's
Jomo Kenyatta International Airport since arriving from Uganda on
Tuesday, when she was refused permission to board Kenya Airway's
flight to Burundi. Burundi authorities advised Kenyan authorities
they would refuse landing permission to any plane carrying her.
   Mrs. Bagaza refused Kenya's invitation to stay at a hotel in the
capital, Nairobi, and continue her negotiations with Burundi
officials from there, the Burundi statement said.
   Bagaza has made several attempts to return home since his
ouster, which occurred while he was on official business in Canada.
Each time, Burundi's new leader, army Maj. Pierre Buyoya, has
closed the airport.
   Bagaza's wife was with him at the time of the coup, but their
four daughters, ages 9 to 13, were in Burundi.
   Burundi's ambassador to Kenya, Marc Nteturuye, reiterated
Burundi's offer to send Bagaza's children to him if he supplied his
address and told the government who should supervise the children
during the trip.
   ``The government of Burundi has waited and is still waiting for
an emissary to come to take the children,'' the government
statement said. ``Bagaza, instead of making a formal request to the
government of Burundi, has chosen this sensational method in
sending his wife to go on a hunger strike in the Nairobi airport
lounge.''
   Authorities refused to allow reporters into the airport to
interview Mrs. Bagaza. The African Lawyers Association has charged
the Bagaza children are living under bad conditions in Burundi.
Burundi denies that.
</TEXT>
