<HEAD>Cities Sizzle Through Heat Wave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A heat wave has caused a run on electric fans and
watermelons in the eastern cities of Nanjing and Shanghai, official
reports said Saturday.
   Temperatures have hovered at 100 degrees for the past week in
Nanjing with little relief at night, the Xinhua News Agency said.
   Shanghai on Friday recorded its second hottest day in 37 years
when the mercury rose to 99 degrees. The record was 100 degrees,
set in 1978.
   Television news showed Shanghai residents sleeping on cots
outside in hopes of catching a breeze. Xinhua said Nanjing
residents were doing the same.
   Sales of watermelons, China's favorite summer treat, have
soared, and prices in Nanjing have more than doubled, to about 8
cents a pound, Xinhua said.
   It quoted a salesman at the Xinjiekou Department Store in
Nanjing as saying they sold 1,000 electric fans on Friday alone and
that fan sales were five times higher than last year's.
