<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeachesClosed     07-09 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beaches Closed,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beaches Closed By Waste Reopen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials today reopened beaches along the south
shore of Long Island that were closed for as many as three days
after needles, blood vials and other debris washed up on shore.
   Federal and state investigators said Friday that the debris that
had closed 25 miles of beaches did not appear to be hospital wastes
as originally thought, but instead looked like household and
boating garbage.
   Jones Beach, Robert Moses State Park and beaches on Fire Island
were reopened today to weekend beachgoers.
   City Health Commissioner Dr. Stephen C. Joseph said Friday that
the waste that washed up on a seven-mile beach in the city's
borough of Queens, causing officials to close it Friday, did appear
to be medical in origin. But Stern said today that the debris
seemed to be of ``local origin'' _ or syringes used by drug addicts.
   Joseph and New York City Parks Commissioner Henry J. Stern said
the evening tide Friday and the morning tide today brought nothing
new and the beach was reopened.
   Ron Foley, the Long Island regional director for state parks,
said officials searched Jones Beach, which was reopened Friday
afternoon, and Robert Moses Beach this morning and found no other
waste.
   Foley said he believed the problem with the waste washing ashore
is over.
   Debris that collected since Wednesday on the Long Island beaches
included fewer than three dozen syringes of the type used for
insulin injections, three blood vials, vials associated with the
drug crack and some plastic tubing of an uncertain source, said
James Marshall, a spokesman for the federal Environmental
Protection Agency.
   ``We don't believe this is the result of illegally dumped
hospital waste,'' said Randy Braun, an EPA worker who examined the
ocean water from a helicopter.
   Ice cream sticks were mistaken for tongue-depressors, a
carpenter's mask was thought to be a surgical mask and a pair of
household rubber gloves used by a lifeguard to pick up wastes from
the beach were taken for surgical gloves, said August V. Sellitto,
an assistant to U.S. Attorney Andrew J. Maloney of Brooklyn
Borough, who has been investigating the episode.
   Eight miles of Long Island beaches in the town of Bablyon were
closed Friday for the first time. In addition, Long Island's Tobay
Beach and six small beaches on Fire Island were closed for the
second day.
   In Long Island's Nassau County, health department tests of the
ocean water indicated it was in good to excellent condition, with
minimal risks for bathers. Additional tests are planned for the
weekend, the department said.
   The garbage recovered from the beaches will be turned over to
the U.S. attorney's office to determine whether it can be traced
and whether criminal charges are appropriate, said U.S. Rep. Thomas
Downey, D-N.Y.
   Twice in the last month, vials of blood that washed up on the
nearby New Jersey shore were found to contain traces of the AIDS
virus. The source of the vials has not been traced.
</TEXT>
