<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RushmoreFire 1astLd-Writethru a0505 07-09 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rushmore Fire, 1ast Ld - Writethru, a0505,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crews Close To Containing Black Hills Forest Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs the 3rd graf to CORRECT that 100 firefighters are only
part of the force of some 1,200.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET BROKAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUSTER, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters dug with picks and shovels
today to finish the last three miles of fire line around a
16,500-acre forest fire near Mount Rushmore that stopped growing
after thundershowers dampened the area.
   ``We're looking at 90 percent containment this morning,'' said
Dennis Neill, fire information officer. ``We got some good work
done last night.''
   Today's forecast was for warmer, drier weather, he said. But on
Friday thundershowers lifted the spirits of the estimated 1,200
people fighting the fire south of Mount Rushmore National Memorial.
About 100 of the men and women concentrated on finishing the fire
line today.
   ``With the combination of the lower temperature, lower wind
speeds, higher relative humidity and the rain, I'd say we got a
significant amount of help on the fire,'' fire information officer
Jerry Hagen said.
   Lightning is believed to have started the fire Monday night in
Custer State Park. It spread Wednesday into the Black Hills
National Forest and briefly threatened Mount Rushmore and the town
of Keystone.
   Twenty-seven miles of fire line were complete this morning,
Neill said. Smoke from the fire was no longer visible in Custer,
about four miles away.
   Hagen said one drawback to the thunderstorms was lightning that
could cause new fires, but he added: ``If we get some moisture
along with the lightning, I think we'll be hitting it pretty good.''
   Thirty families living along French Creek Road outside the west
boundary of the park were allowed to return home at their own risk
today, but the area remained closed to the public.
   Residents were ordered to evacuate Friday after flames jumped a
highway on the southwest edge of the fire. Officials said the
flames had burned within 1{ miles of some of the homes.
   Custer State Park remained closed to the public with police
stationed at the entrances.
   Crews for Black Hills Power & Light Co. returned to the park
Friday to restore electrical service. Electricity was shut off
Wednesday night to prevent any live lines from falling on fire
crews, said Joe Rovere, a company spokesman. He said at least 30
utility poles would have to be replaced.
</TEXT>
