<DOCNO> AP880709-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HowardProfile     07-09 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Howard Profile,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Spokesman Gets Good Marks For Handling Iran Airliner
Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-US Policy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard admits he is no
expert on the high technology of the Iranian airliner crisis but,
after more than 15 years in the State Department and at the White
House, neither is he any stranger to dealing with reporters in
times of trouble.
   For nearly 2{ hours during the past week, Howard fielded
questions in the cramped Pentagon briefing room about such things
as transponders, air corridors, black boxes and the differences
between Mode 2 and Mode 3 electronic signals.
   He had been a State Department public affairs officer dealing
with the Philippines when President Ferdinand Marcos was forced
from office.
   He had been spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Cyprus when Shiite
gunmen seized a TWA airliner and killed Navy diver Robert Stethem.
   He had been expelled from Poland for his contacts with Polish
intellectuals after the Warsaw government declared martial law in
1981.
   He had been a stand-in spokesman at the White House at the
height of the Iran-Contra crisis.
   But nothing in his career had been quite like this.
   ``It's a very different environment from the White House,'' he
said in an interview. ``Everybody has an opinion and a point of
view, and the place is so big, there are so many points of view,
there are so many kinds of experts, and not all those experts
agree. ... And so we have the battle of the experts in the briefing
room some of the time.
   ``The long-time news people here are the ones that, on some
issues, it's very difficult to deal with, because you end up
getting a counterbriefing from the floor.''
   In the give-and-take, Howard sometimes simply has told reporters
that their questions go beyond his technical knowledge, saying, for
example, ``I am not the final authority on widths of air
corridors.''
   ``I am simply trying to explain the matter the best I can with
the information available to me,'' he said Thursday.
   Television, newspaper and magazine reporters covering the
Pentagon generally agree that he has done a good job, although to
some he seemed a bit impatient at times.
   ``He gets testy over some things, as most any briefing officer
does, but by and large he tries to be helpful,'' said Carl
Rochelle, Pentagon correspondent for Cable News Network. ``He tries
to answer your questions. If he can't answer them, he tries to make
it clear to you that he can't answer them, and sometimes he even
tries to help when he can't answer.''
   Bruce van Voorst, national security correspondent for Time
magazine, said, ``I`m amazed that Dan dares to stand up in front of
that crowd out there, which is for the most part a pretty
professional operation, and talk about Mode 2 or Mode 3 operations
and that sort of stuff. He has obviously made every effort to at
least become reasonably familiar with the technical issues he was
talking about.''
   David Evans, Pentagon correspondent of the Chicago Tribune,
said, ``I was very pleased on Tuesday that he took an hour to have,
I think, a viable exchange with the assembled reporters.''
   The twice-weekly Pentagon briefings usually last about half an
hour. Tuesday's was roughly an hour and Thursday's was more than 80
minutes, almost entirely devoted to the shooting down of an Iranian
Airbus by the U.S. cruiser Vincennes on Sunday.
   ``This is not the kind of a story that any spokesman likes to
deal with, of course, but all you can do is the best you can,''
said Howard.
   The spokesman, 45, from Chattanooga, Tenn., is married and has
three children, the oldest a boy studying astronomy at Boston
University. His wife, Mary, a real estate agent, watched him brief
on Thursday for the first time.
   Although he may not know everything about transponders, Howard,
does have some technological expertise he can call upon. He is an
old car buff, and likes to fix them up himself.
   The airliner incident and the current investigation of Defense
Department procurement are the biggest stories he has had to handle
since he came to the Pentagon in February as assistant secretary of
defense for public affairs from his previous post as a deputy White
House press secretary.
   The week after the procurement story broke in mid-June, Howard
had planned to go on vacation. He hasn't had the vacation yet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
