<DOCNO> AP880709-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-StaffWars Bjt   07-09 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Staff Wars, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Vice Presidential, Campaign Staffs Sometimes At Odds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Because he is vice president as well as the
certain Republican presidential nominee, George Bush must contend
with twin staffs. And insiders say the two sometimes-feuding
factions have produced an ongoing tug-of-war over policy.
   A sharing of responsibility for Bush's daily activity between
chief of staff Craig Fuller and campaign manager Lee Atwater is
causing tensions within the Bush operation, according to campaign
officials, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   And while Bush has a committee of six trusted advisers to
oversee the broad strokes of his campaign, advisers claim that turf
battles are likely to continue until the vacant seat at the end of
the table is occupied.
   That's the chair reserved for the still-unfilled post of
campaign chairman, presumably being left open for Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III.
   ``At this point, with all due respect to everybody who's down
there, the final decision-maker is not in the room,'' said
Republican consultant Eddie Mahe, a Bush campaign adviser.
   Although officials in recent days have made efforts to smooth
over differences _ including a well-publicized strategy session
last week among President Reagan, Bush and top White House and
campaign aides _ Bush campaign workers still report some rough
going in the coordination department.
   Atwater is in charge of Bush's campaign staff and oversees all
political activity. Fuller, who works out of Bush's vice
presidential office in the Old Executive Office Building and is on
the public payroll, deals with the official vice presidential side
of Bush's routine, including scheduling.
   However, insiders said that Fuller has far more input over the
entire Bush operation, including all details of campaign
appearances and policy, than organizational charts might suggest.
   ``Fuller has got the keys,'' said a Bush campaign adviser
familiar with Bush's campaign operations.
   The adviser said Fuller has enormous say on all matters dealing
with Bush's schedule. And these days, Bush's schedule, not
surprisingly, is mostly political.
   ``Often, it gets to be a real bureaucratic problem,'' said the
adviser, who declined to be identified by name.
   Fuller and Atwater said no frictions exist and suggested that
the Bush campaign is well oiled.
   But officials in both offices claim privately that while Fuller
and Atwater make a show of working together, there are many times
when one side of the operation doesn't know what the other side is
doing.
   Frustrations about a lack of such coordination prompted the
former campaign communications director, Peter Teeley, to quit his
job in May.
   For one thing, until recently Bush had two separate press staffs
_ one answerable to Atwater, the other to Fuller.
   Now, all campaign-related inquiries are fielded through the
office of Shelia Tate, Bush's new press secretary, who said she has
``unbridled input and access'' to Bush.
   One of her first acts was to put a halt to the mailing of Bush
campaign speeches to news organizations by the office of the vice
president _ at taxpayers' expense.
   James Lake, Bush's senior communications adviser, said there
still may be glitches, but fewer than before. ``Sometimes, the
campaign may seem top heavy. But that's what's required if it's
going to work.''
   David Carmen, a GOP consultant, said that fragmented
jurisdiction is not new with the Bush campaign. ``The Reagan
campaign had a lot of factions. I'm sure it's frustrating for
everybody involved, but they both (Atwater and Fuller) have valid
perspectives.''
   However, Carmen said, Bush should ``leave the campaigning to
Atwater and the scheduling to Fuller. Then they'll be in good
shape.''
   The campaign is overseen by a sort of board of directors,
composed of Fuller, Atwater, media consultant Roger Ailes, pollster
Robert Teeter and two close friends of Bush, former New Jersey Sen.
Nicholas Brady and Texas oilman Robert Mossbacher.
   The group meets, sometimes as frequently as once a week, to
discuss strategy.
   According to Fuller, general concepts of the vice president's
schedule are discussed at these meetings, but not the details,
which he said are worked out between himself and Atwater.
   Ed Rogers, deputy to Atwater, said that ``we've done all right
so far'' in seeking to coordinate the different roles of the office
of vice president and the campaign office. In the meetings of the
six campaign officials, ``everybody brings a unique set of
responsibilities to the table,'' he said.
   Treasury Secretary Baker is expected to join the campaign around
the time of the Republican convention Aug. 15-18.
   Meanwhile, friction between an official staff and a campaign
staff ``come with the territory'' when an incumbent is running
either for re-election or for higher office, said GOP consultant
Mahe.
   ``There are going to be misunderstandings, there is going to be
confusion, there are going to be personality battles, there are
going to be ego wars,'' Mahe said.
   ``But it will never be as brutal as it is to deal with an
incumbent U.S. senator. Because at least here, the two staffs may
be in different buildings but the buildings are only four blocks
apart. When you've got an omnipotent U.S. senator's staff and a
poor campaign staff out in the state someplace, then you have real
double grief.''
</TEXT>
