<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Family Compensation Considered In Iran Plane Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6-7th grafs, While Bush, with 4 grafs to update with
Nebraska GOP convention, include dates of Democratic convention.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CARL C. CRAFT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush rules out paying reparations to
Iran's government but says the Reagan administration is considering
compensating families of the 290 people killed when the U.S. Navy
shot down an Iranian jetliner. Michael Dukakis says ``some form of
humanitarian assistance would probably be appropriate.''
   Bush, the Republican presidential nominee-to-be, said Friday in
Atlanta he feels ``terribly sad for the families of those people''
who died in the downing of the Iranian passenger plane by an
American warship in the Persian Gulf last Sunday.
   ``I would never, ever under any circumstances offer reparations
to the Iranian government,'' Bush said. He added that he
understands payments to the victims' families are being considered
by the administration.
   In Washington, President Reagan also said the question of
compensating the families is among matters ``under consideration.''
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said there were ``still some
open questions'' on the compensation issue.
   Dukakis indicated Friday in Texas that he favors payments to the
families. ``I think some form of humanitarian assistance would
probably be appropriate,'' said the Massachusetts governor and
likely Democratic presidential nominee.
   Bush told Nebraska Republicans today via a telephone hookup that
polls showing people think Dukakis is more conservative than he is
are ``crazy, nutty.''
   Speaking from Washington, D.C., to more than 300 delegates of
the state GOP, Bush said Dukakis is a ``card-carrying member of the
American Civil Liberties Union,'' while ``I am a card-carrying
member of the National Rifle Association.''
   Dukakis planned to campaign in California, Oregon and
Washington. Jesse Jackson scheduled a meeting in San Francisco with
supporters of his Democratic presidential campaign.
   Republicans were continuing their unity rally today in Atlanta,
scene of the Democratic National Convention July 18-25, and
prepared to hear from Bush's former rivals Bob Dole of Kansas,
Senate GOP leader, and Rep. Jack Kemp of New York.
   Addressing the Republican rally Friday, Bush stressed national
defense policy and said ``multilateralism seems to be my opponent's
answer to Soviet aggression.'' Bush contended Dukakis would leave
the United States generally depending on the United Nations to
maintain peace in the world.
   At a news conference before the rally, Bush, questioned at
length about whether his campaign was properly repaying the
government for the cost of his campaign trips on Air Force planes,
maintained ``we are not abusing the public trust.''
   Bush may have used tax money on campaign trips, Democratic
National Chairman Paul Kirk said Friday at a news conference in
Atlanta, where he questioned whether the vice president can travel
in the next month without violating spending limits.
   Bush called Kirk's allegation ``an outrageous charge.''
   Dukakis, meanwhile, was still searching for a vice presidential
choice and campaigned in Texas with one potential running mate,
Sen. Lloyd M. Bentsen Jr. of Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee. ``I'm pondering,'' Dukakis said of Bentsen at a rally
Friday in Texarkana.
   When asked if he wanted the job, Bentsen seemed to play down the
possibility. ``I don't think we have to worry about that,'' Bentsen
said.
   In Dallas, Jackson said Friday that his campaign does not have
any veto power in Dukakis' hunt for someone to share the Democratic
ticket and does not ``choose to exercise the appearance as though
we have a veto over anyone in the process.''
   Dukakis, responding to news from Washington that the nation's
civilian unemployment rate dropped in June to a 14-year low of 5.3
percent, said the figures masked economic suffering.
   ``National unemployment rates don't tell you a great deal about
what is happening in communities and neighborhoods and regions
across this country,'' Dukakis said. ``For one thing, a great many
of these jobs are low-wage jobs, many of them paying no more than
$7,000, $7,500 a year. They don't have health insurance,'' he added.
</TEXT>
