<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Malaysia-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru   07-09 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Malaysia-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0480,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede KUALA LUMPUR</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shultz Arrives in Indonesia For Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds:UPDATES throughout with Shultz arrival in Indonesia, details
on Malaysian talks. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
met Indonesian officials and said he discussed human rights with
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad of Malaysia today during his last
official trip to Asia.
   Shultz arrived in Jakarta for talks with President Suharto and
other officials about informal talks scheduled July 25 in the
Indonesian capital aimed at a political settlement of the Cambodian
war.
   Earlier today, in the Malaysian capital of Kuala Lumpur, Shultz
met with Mahathir for three hours and said the Malaysian leader
assured him prisoners detained without trial in Malaysian jails
would be accorded their full rights.
   Twenty-eight U.S. congressmen, the Washington-based Asia Watch
human rights group and the New York City-based Lawyers Committee
for Human Rights asked Shultz to bring up concerns over detentions
under Malaysia's Internal Security Act in his talks with Mahathir,
the two human rights groups said.
   The act allows the government to arrest and detain people
without trial indefinitely.
   Last fall, the prime minister ordered the arrest of 106 people
critical of his government _ including the leader of the opposition
in Parliament, Lim Kit Siang. He said then that their arrests were
necessary because they had instigated racial clashes between the
country's Malays and ethnic Chinese.
   ``The subject was discussed ... fundamentally in a satisfactory
way,'' Shultz said, speaking to a news conference before leaving
for Jakarta, Indonesia.
   ``We took note that 71 people have been released and that the
prime minister and foreign minister assured me that that those
remaining under detention would be accorded full statutory and
constitutional rights and as time went on we would see them dealt
with properly,'' said Shultz.
   But on Friday, the Malaysian House of Representatives voted to
strengthen the security act so that detainees can no longer
challenge in court the reasons for their detention in court.
   When Mahathir became prime minister in July 1981, about 550
people were held without trial in Malaysian prisons.
   Shultz arrived in Malaysia from Bangkok, Thailand, where he held
talks with the foreign ministers of the member countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
   In Jakarta, he was met at the military airport by the defense
minister, Gen. L.B. Murdani. Shultz will hold talks with Suharto
and Foreign Minister Ali Alatas before leaving for the Philippines
Monday.
   Shultz also will visit Hong Kong, China, South Korea, Japan and
new Marshall Islands republic in the Pacific on the trip.
   Indonesia will be the host of informal talks between Cambodia's
Vietnam-backed government and three guerrilla groups. The
guerrillas have been fighting the government and Vietnamese troops
since Vietnam invaded in 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
