<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Rehabilitation     07-09 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Rehabilitation,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Step Taken In Rehabilitation of Bukharin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party has readmitted Nikolai I.
Bukharin, a major Bolshevik theorist, and more than a dozen others
shot during purges under Josef Stalin a half-century ago, Tass
reported Saturday.
   Bukharin had been cleared in February of trumped-up spying
charges for which he was shot in 1938. But the second step in his
rehabilitation, restoration to party rolls, was not taken until now.
   Political rehabilitation had been expected, because Bukharin's
moderate economic program contains elements similar to those being
implemented by Soviet leader Mikahil S. Gorbachev.
   But in today's Communist Party announcement, the official news
agency said a special commission of the party's ruling Politburo
found that Bukharin and an associate, Alexei I. Rykov, had made
mistakes.
   ``However, their mistakes and dissenting positions are not of an
anti-party character,'' the commission said.
   The Tass dispatch did not detail the mistakes Bukharin and Rykov
had made.
   In the 1920s, Bukharin favored a continuation of Soviet founder
Vladimir Lenin's New Economic Policy, which permitted some private
enterprise and left farms in the hands of the peasants. Bukharin
hoped to encourage farmers to combine property voluntarily and move
onto collective farms.
   Gorbachev's reforms also allow some private enterprise and
families to lease farmland from their collective and state farms
and till the soil themselves.
   Last November, Gorbachev announced that the drive to
rehabilitate the millions of victims of Stalin's purges would
resume. Stalin ruled from 1924 to his death in 1953.
   Tass said the Politburo commission heard a report from the party
control committee saying Bukharin and Rykov, expelled from the
party in March 1937, were readmitted June 21. The news agency did
not explain why it took 2{ weeks to announce the action.
   Fourteen other victims of Stalin's purges who had been tried
along with Bukharin and Rykov were also restored to party rolls,
Tass said.
</TEXT>
