<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Soviets-Hungary     07-09 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Hungary,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Says Soviets Preparing Troop Pullout From Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intelligence reports indicate the Soviet Union
may be ready to withdraw up to 65,000 troops from Hungary,
according to a senior State Department official.
   A pullout from the East European country has long been a subject
of speculation here and in Western allied capitals. Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev has already begun pulling back in Afghanistan
while Soviet-backed Vietnam has announced a troop withdrawal in
Cambodia.
   The U.S. official, who briefed reporters Friday under rules of
anonymity, said the United States would welcome the Hungary
pullout. He said Gorbachev may have already passed the word about
it to Warsaw Pact leaders.
   Last year Gorbachev set the stage for a nuclear missile
reduction treaty with the United States by announcing Soviet
short-range rockets would be withdrawn from Eastern Europe.
   The prospective move on Hungary could be a preliminary step to a
Soviet acceptance of Western terms for holding wide-ranging
negotiations to reduce conventional troops and armor concentrations
in Europe.
   At the same time, the Soviet leader is faced with growing unrest
in several Eastern countries, including Hungary, where economic
conditions are falling short of workers' expectations.
   A recent change in government in Budapest seemed to indicate
Hungary, in some ways the most liberalized of the communist states,
was about to embark on a reform program matching Gorbachev's
perestroika policies at home.
   In Prague on Friday, Soviet Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov repeated a
Kremlin proposal to withdraw the Red Army from all foreign
territory by the year 2000.
   But the Soviet government chief told Western reporters that such
moves could come only in the context of a general withdrawal _
involving other nations as well as the Soviet Union.
   ``Our proposal is this: let us take out all the armies,'' he
said. ``The armies in Czechoslovakia are part of the Warsaw Pact
armies. Let us agree on a radical solution in the West and in the
East.''
</TEXT>
