<HEAD>Three Die in Hotel Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASCO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire raced through an old, two-story
wood-frame hotel early today, killing three people, as nearly a
dozen other fires broke out in this small city in south-central
Washington state, officials said.
   Fire officials said arson was to blame for all of the fires
except the one that destroyed the hotel which was used as
apartments for low-income residents.
   In addition to the three dead, Assistant Fire Chief John Fifer
said one person was seriously burned. Firemen searched the rubble
for other possible victims; 20 to 25 people were reported to have
lived in the building.
   Fifer said the four victims were males, but added that their
identities and ages were not available.
   Firefighters were kept busy chasing from fire to fire, Fire
Chief Larry Dickinson said. About 10 fires broke out in garbage
bins, brush along fence lines and in another apartment 20 blocks
from the destroyed hotel.
   The fires at the second apartment building were set in a garbage
can and a laundry room, but were quickly extinguished, said fire
officials.
   A state fire marshall was called in to investigate the fatal
fire, Fifer said.
