<1ST_LINE>u p AM-GOP-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0545 07-09 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Rally In Atlanta Just Before Democrats Arrive For
Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf bgng ``Martinez said ... '' to refer to
analogy rather than double entendre.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican leaders on Saturday took turns
assailing Michael Dukakis in a rally just nine days before
Democrats gather in the same city nominate the Massachusetts
Governor for president.
   ``If you're undertaxed, vote for Dukakis. If you're overtaxed
... we want you in our party,'' proclaimed Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.,
one of several of Vice President George Bush's former challengers
for the GOP nomination.
   Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., another former contender, said, ``We're
not going to run around this country and try to bloody up the
opposition. But let's contain (Dukakis) to Massachusetts.''
   The rally was the third in a series designed to raise money and
demonstrate Republican solidarity. The first two were in Denver and
Cincinnati.
   The theme of this weekend's meeting was winning the South. Bush
kicked off the weekend with a speech to a Friday night rally,
predicting the South would be solid for Republicans in November.
   Playing on a theme the GOP will use repeatedly in the South, he
attacked Dukakis' national defense policy as too reliant on U.S.
allies and not strong enough on nuclear arms and the Star Wars
missile defense system.
   `We don't want to rain on the Democrats' parade, they'll do it
by themselves,` Bush said, evoking cheers and laughter from the
partisan crowd.
   Some of the South's top elected Republicans joined in the rally
with appearances Saturday, including South Carolina Gov. Carroll
Campbell, Sen. Strom Thurmond, also from South Carolina, Gov. Bob
Martinez of Florida, and Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky.
   Thurmond called Dukakis ``a mere midget compared to George
Bush.''
   Martinez said the differences in experience between Bush and
Dukakis amounted to ``the tale of the tall and the short,'' using
the same analogy as Thurmond, referring to the difference in height
between the two candidates.
   ``Can you imagine the folly of them coming down South and
holding their convention?'' said Lee Atwater, Bush's national
campaign manager and a South Carolina native, in his speech
Saturday.
   Atwater said the convention would serve to highlight issues
where Dukakis' record would cost him votes in the South, including
that as governor he has been ``dumb enough to raise taxes in the
middle of a campaign.''
   Dukakis' support of gun control, opposition to the death
penalty, and the problems with Massachusetts' prison furlough
program also would make Dukakis unpalatable to Southernors, he said.
   Atwater said Dukakis' indecision on a running mate was ``making
Hamlet look like the rock of Gibralter.''
   ``After the rest of the public gets to know him (Dukakis) in the
South, this guy couldn't get elected dog catcher down here,'' he
said.
   Dole said Dukakis is ``simply embarrassed by American power.''
   ``Have you heard him say one kind word about President Reagan's
arms control triumph in Moscow?'' he said, referring to
implementation of the U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium and
shorter-range nuclear missiles.
   Bush did not attend Saturday's sessions, flying off late Friday
for his home in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   Despite the rhetoric, Atwater predicted that Bush would fall in
the polls following the Democratic National Convention because of
all the media attention Dukakis will receive. He said most voters
would not decide until the final weeks of the campaign, and then
voters will move to Bush when they find out ``what an honest,
decent fellow he is.''
</TEXT>
