<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0438 07-09 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Criticizes Democrats on Drug Issues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 8 grafs from Reagan radio speech; picks up 3rd
graf, Before Reagan.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, saying that ``the time for
excuses and delays is long past,'' appealed to Democrats in
Congress today to appoint members to a task force aimed at
stripping politics from the national drug debate.
   In his weekly radio address, delivered from the Oval Office, the
president also disclosed that White House employes were given
notice on Friday that random drug testing will begin in 60 days.
   Reagan recounted the formation of ``Just Say No'' clubs as part
of first lady Nancy Reagan's anti-drug campaign among youth, and
said, ``I figure if young people across the country can come
together against illegal drugs, then why shouldn't the grown-ups in
Washington be able to do the same?''
   ``In May, I proposed that both houses of Congress, both sides of
the aisle, join together with our administration in a bipartisan
executive-legislative task force to advance America's uniform
anti-drug policy.''
   ``If we are going to get the drugs out of schools, we need to
get the politics out of drugs,'' he said.
   ``I believe that partisan bickering or seeking political
advantage can only impede our progress in seeking to achieve a
drug-free America,'' the president said.
   ``I hope that the Democratic leaders in Congress will now join
in this united effort,'' he said. ``The time for excuses and delays
is long past.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FOLLOWING GRAF EMBAGOED FOR 1:06 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In the Democratic response to the president's speech, Rep.
Charles B. Rangel of New York, chairman of the House Committee on
Narcotics Abuse and Control, also discussed the drug issue, saying
that outgoing Attorney General Edwin Meese III had ``failed the
American people by not putting together the type of cabinet team
necessary to start the fight in the war on drugs.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>END EMBARGOED MATERIAL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Before Reagan prodded Democrats to get on board his joint
executive-legislative task force, presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater voiced hope that the appointments would still be made.
   Asked why Democrats had not yet done so, Fitzwater said: ``Well,
we believe they will ... because they've expressed interest in the
drug issue, they have said they care about it and would like to
develop some initiative. ...
   ``They're waiting to get reports from their committee chairmen
and others who are advising them. I just can't imagine, after all
the talk they've made around the country on drugs, that they
wouldn't want to participate.''
   Reagan said May 16 in a speech to the graduating class of the
Coast Guard Academy that the national drug policy debate had become
too politicized. At the time, he called on Democratic and
Republican members of Congress to join the executive branch on a
task force to recommend solutions.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., and House Minority
Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., named members of their chambers to
the task force some time ago.
   But House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and Senate Majority
Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., have not named their members.
   Reagan had said in the Coast Guard address that little headway
could be made in the effort to combat drug abuse and drug
trafficking so long as national debate on the issue took on
partisan tones.
   Reagan did direct the members of the task force to concentrate
on strategies aimed at attacking demand for illegal narcotics. The
president had said in the past that interdiction efforts would be
futile so long as demand continued unabated.
   The president sent his marching orders to the
executive-legislative task force as Republican senators unveiled a
$1.5-billion-a-year anti-drug plan that would install a top drug
enforcement officer in the president's Cabinet, deny federal
benefits to users and allow the death penalty for convicted dealers.
   The measure, sponsored by Dole and 10 GOP colleagues, also would
boost the drug-enforcement authority of the Border Patrol and
Forest Service, launch a federal initiative against gangs and crack
down on illegal use of firearms.
   In his statement, Reagan said: ``Much has already been done, but
there is much more to do. The task force offers us the rare
opportunity to lift the battle above politics, to make broad
progress with bipartisan policy. ... We must not rest until the
message to every drug user is clear: We mean business. No more
drugs.''
</TEXT>
