<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Malaysia-Detainees 1stLd-Writethru   07-09 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Malaysia-Detainees, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0470,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Tightens Law On Detention Without Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs with Shultz visit, comments on human
rights. Pickup 4th pvs, ``The official ...'' Minor editing
thereafter to TRIM and CONFORM</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Representatives voted
to strengthen the Internal Security Act, which allows the
government to arrest and detain people without trial indefinitely.
   The House passed the law Friday and sent it to the Senate.
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz visited Malaysia today
and said he discussed human rights issues with Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad.
   Last fall, the prime minister ordered the arrest of 106 people
critical of his government _ including the leader of the opposition
in Parliament, Lim Kit Siang. Mahathir said then that their arrests
were necessary because they had instigated racial clashes between
the country's Malays and ethnic Chinese.
   ``The subject was discussed ... fundamentally in a satisfactory
way,'' Shultz said at a news conference before leaving for Jakarta,
Indonesia.
   ``We took note that 71 people have been released and that the
prime minister and foreign minister assured me that that those
remaining under detention would be accorded full statutory and
constitutional rights and as time went on we would see them dealt
with properly,'' said Shultz.
   Twenty-eight U.S. congressmen, the Washington-based Asia Watch
human rights group and the New York City-based Lawyers Committee
for Human Rights had asked Shultz to bring up American concerns
over the detentions with Mahathir, according to the two human
rights groups.
   The official Bernama news agency reported that the amendments
passed by the House, among other things, ``prohibited any action,
suit, prosecution, or any other legal proceedings from being
brought, instituted or maintained in respect of any detention.''
   Forty-seven representatives supported the amendments and 18 were
opposed. The amendments will go to the Senate for approval later
this month and then to the king before they become law.
   The Senate is dominated by government appointees, and the king,
like Britain's Queen Elizabeth, is a constitutional head and
normally signs all laws passed by the legislature.
   ``By completely depriving the right of the people to seek legal
redress in court, the situation is worse than during the colonial
days,'' former foreign minister Rais Yatim, a governing party
member who opposes Mahathir, said during the parliamentary debate.
   Malaysia won independence from Britain in 1957 and inherited the
Internal Security Act from the days of colonial rule.
   Lee Lam Thai, acting leader of the parliamentary opposition,
said the amendments would prohibit anyone who has been improperly
detained from asking a court to secure his release.
   Deputy Home Affairs Minister Megat Junid Megat Ayub said during
the debate the government would not abuse its powers and that the
Internal Security Act was necessary for the security of the country.
   The U.S. congressmen and human rights groups have called for the
detainees to be brought to trial or released.
   About 80 people now are being held under the act. When Mahathir
became prime minister in July 1981, more than 500 people were under
detention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
