<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-Security 1stLd-Writethru   07-09 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Security, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0546,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tighter Security Measures Imposed Following Bombings</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with explosion at hockey
clubhouse, police helicopter at rugby match. Picks up 2nd graf pvs,
`Last weekend...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used mine detectors
Saturday to check cars arriving at a Pretoria rugby stadium as part
of tightened security measures following a series of bombings.
   A mine attached to a telephone pole exploded outside the
clubhouse of a field hockey team in a Johannesburg suburb. No
serious injuries were reported.
   At a rugby match in Cape Town, a police helicopter circled the
stadium.
   Last weekend, a car bomb exploded outside a Johannesburg stadium
as spectators left a rugby match. Two people died and 35 were
injured. Other recent targets included a video game arcade and a
beachfront restaurant.
   On Saturday, a large police contingent was on duty at Pretoria's
main rugby stadium. Spectators arriving for the game were searched
as they entered the grounds, and mine detectors were used to scan
underneath vehicles entering parking lots.
   Police have blamed the recent bombings on the outlawed African
National Congress guerrilla movement, which has neither claimed nor
denied responsibility. The ANC is the main group fighting to
overthrow South Africa's government.
   Authorities across the country have launched a ``bomb awareness
campaign'' to encourage greater public vigilance. City officials in
Johannesburg are publicizing a special emergency telephone number
to be used for reporting suspected bombs, and the Cape Town Chamber
of Commerce has published a set of security guidelines to
shopowners.
   Even before the bombings intensified over the past four months,
posters were on display in many government buildings to help the
public identify limpet mines, one of the devices most commonly used
in the bomb attacks.
</TEXT>
