<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Eastern     07-09 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Point To Firings, Suspensions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines union leaders say a new safety
agreement with the carrier could be a sign of progress, but add
that tense labor-management relations will improve more if the high
number of firings and suspensions is reduced.
   ``We've had five terminations this week, so nothing has
abated,'' said Nancy Currier, a vice president of the Transport
Workers Union local representing 7,000 flight attendants. The rate
of firings ``is far higher than it was last year, and far higher
than it was before (Frank) Lorenzo.
   ``It would be one of the most meaningful areas for improvement.''
   Lorenzo's Texas Air Corp. took over Eastern more than two years
ago, inheriting some $2.5 billion in debts and a recent history of
labor-management conflict.
   At the district office of the Machinists union, Eastern's
largest with 12,000 mechanics, baggage handlers and ramp workers,
union officials keep detailed charts tracing the steady rise of
disciplinary measures, particularly firings, since the takeover.
   ``Our big concern is the unjust terminations. Lorenzo talks
about mending fences, but I don't think the word has filtered down
to his front-line management, who keep burning bridges,'' said Rick
Iacino, a Machinists general chairman.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said Eastern wouldn't comment on
the safety agreement announced Wednesday in Washington beyond a
statement from President Phil Bakes.
   While Bakes praised the agreement as important to separating
safety from other issues, he said a ``missing link'' remains until
contract negotiations are completed with the Machinists, who have
been in federal mediation for seven months, and the pilots, with
whom talks started about a month ago.
   Former Labor Secretary William Brock, who brought the two sides
together in Washington, said battling between Eastern management
and its union leadership threatens the carrier's survival.
   ``It is the commitment of labor and management leaders which
will make or break this effort,'' Brock said. ``Frankly, this
presents some cause for concern.''
   ``All observers have said when looking at this that they've
never seen anything this severe and such shrill treatment between
management and labor _ maybe going back to the '40s and the coal
miners,'' said veteran Machinists leader Charles E. Bryan.
   The agreement calls for more outside, impartial scrutiny,
increased communications between labor and management, and promises
no reprisals against employees who point out safety problems.
   The Machinists claim that employees who balked at hurry-up work
have been disciplined; in addition, workers have been fired for
insubordination, refusing to work excessive overtime or for union
activities.
   The Machinists union has had 41 shop stewards fired in the last
two years. This year, 129 Machinists have been fired so far,
compared to 157 in the first six months of 1987, the union says.
   The Machinists say they have fared well in grievances, winning
back pay and reinstatement in a majority of cases. But the
grievance procedures are backlogged more than a year, they say.
   The Air Line Pilots Association, representing 3,500 Eastern
pilots, has had a different problem: many of its pilots have gone
to other airlines or left the industry entirely because of
Eastern's tense situation and uncertain future.
   Pilots spokesman J.B. Stokes said nearly 1,000 pilots will have
left Eastern since 1986 by the end of this summer, according to
projections.
   ``You're talking about 25 percent. Without the pilots, these
planes are taco stands,'' Stokes said.
   Pilots last year launched a MaxSafety program in which they
highlighted alleged safety laxity and took their complaints into
congressional hearings.
   Eastern has said toughened absenteeism policies and increased
discipline are part of efforts to correct years of worker abuses
that have driven up costs. Management has indicated it still
believes cuts in labor costs are essential.
   This spring, federal officials conducted special inspections of
aircraft flown by Eastern and Continental Airlines, another Texas
Air subsidiary. They also examined Texas Air's management and
finances.
   They said that they found no unsafe conditions but warned of
possible safety problems because of the labor-management battles.
</TEXT>
