<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-Democrats-Text     07-09 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Democrats-Text,850</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the weekly Democratic
response to President Reagan's radio address, given by Rep. Charles
B. Rangel, D-N.Y.
   I'm Representative Charles Rangel, Chairman of the House Select
Committee on Narcotic Abuse and Control.
   Mr. President, now that Ed Meese has finally resigned as acting
attorney general, you now have the opportunity to appoint a person
that can restore the dignity and integrity that the office
rightfully deserves.
   Ed Meese not only let you down as a personal friend, Mr.
President, but when you made him your personal coordinator in the
war against drugs, there was no strategy, there was no policy. In
short, there was no war.
   You appointed Ed Meese to head up your Drug Policy Abuse Board
composed of your highest ranking Cabinet officials. And yet, Mr.
President, he let us down. With every major drug-producing country
having bumper crops year after year, Mr. Meese has never been able
to persuade our Secretary of State to even place drugs on our
foreign policy agenda.
   On the Middle East, communism, terrorism, arm controls _ we've
all heard the eloquence of our outspoken secretary of state. But
even today, we've yet to hear one word from Secretary of State
George Shultz on narcotics control, as we see drug-traffickers
assassinate international leaders, plunder and corrupt governments,
and even hold fragile democracies in our own hemisphere hostage.
   Even when you, Mr. President, admitted that narcotic abuse and
trafficking was a threat to our national security, it wasn't enough
to get former Secretary of Defense Weinberger or now Secretary
Carlucci to pitch in and lend their support with the multi-trillion
dollar technology we've invested in our military to back up and to
support our Border Patrol, our Coast Guard, and Customs officials.
   Surely Mr. President, the protection of our borders and shores
against the intrusion of this deadly epidemic-causing poison
warrants the support of our sophisticated military leadership. Mr.
President, Mr. Meese and your Drug Policy Board has never been able
to get Secretary Bennett _ Secretary of Education Bennett _ to get
beyond ``just saying no.'' ``No'' to preventive program, ``no'' to
educational programs, and even ``no'' to our local and state
governments as we try to give assistance to formulate their own
programs.
   Today we have no health programs designed for drug abusers from
the secretary of Health and Human Services. We don't have any
health policy that encourages research and treatment modalities to
share with private and public health providers. And throughout
these great United States in this possession, we don't even have
one federal rehabilitation center to serve as a model for our
nation.
   As Mr. Meese was conducting a war against drugs, Mr. President,
he certainly needed more than a Drug Enforcement Agency that
although these are hard-working, dedicated agents that we only have
2,800 agents to cover the entire United States and the foreign
countries that allow their presence.
   Mr. President, the local and state law enforcement officials
know that the federal government can't do this job alone. They have
been in the trenches for nearly eight years, outnumbered, outarmed,
but always on the job. But they've never been invited as full-time
partners in this so-called war against drugs.
   Every budget that has been projected by the Congress to provide
for federal assistance to these dedicated officials have been
rejected or resisted by you, Mr. President, your Office of
Management and Budget, and yes, your attorney general. Now Mr.
President, even after seven-and-a-half years, we can start anew.
   You can now appoint an attorney general that will work with the
Congress and to help us to prepare legislation that can truly make
a national war against drugs, and that can make all Americans
proud. The ever-mounting increase of narcotics that's entering our
classrooms and even our boardrooms indicate that this is not a
local issue, and certainly it can't be considered a Democratic or
Republican issue.
   Let us know, Mr. President, now that as late as it is, we can
appoint an attorney general that will work with Speaker Jim Wright
and his bipartisan House legislative team headed by Democratic
Majority Leader Tom Foley, and Republican Minority Leader Bob
Michels that can fashion a bill and a policy that makes some sense.
For those of us that are faint at heart and who believe that we can
win this war by legalizing drugs, let them be on notice, Mr.
President, that this battle can and shall be won. We can't do it
just by slogans.
   We can't do it by throwing up our hands in frustration and
despair, but we can begin to get started by stop blaming each other
and coming together and working together in a joint effort. With
your new attorney general we can start a new relationship. The
Congress can't do this job alone. It's not too late for us together
to provide the resources, the programs, but most of all, Mr.
President, the leadership to get the job done.
   Thank you.
</TEXT>
