<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LockheedClosure     07-09 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lockheed Closure,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lockheed Closing Plant Opened in Wake of 1965 Watts Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The closing of a Lockheed Aircraft Corp.
plant will end one of the few successful efforts by a major
employer to create jobs in the impoverished Watts neighborhood
following the 1965 riots.
   The Watts-Willowbrook plant, which makes parts for the C-5 cargo
plane, will close by October when work on the C-5 is completed, the
company said Friday. The plant is on the city's south side, about 8
miles from downtown.
   Of the plant's 117 workers, 78 have enough seniority to qualify
for transfers to the company's Burbank plant, about 20 miles away.
Lockheed said it will attempt to find employment for the rest with
other aerospace firms.
   A Lockheed spokesman said the company had expected to use the
plant for other work after the completion of the C-5 program, but
Lockheed's aircraft business has been dwindling and no suitable
projects could be found.
   ``We had hoped that Lockheed would be able to feed more work to
Watts-Willowbrook,'' said Mark Molli, an aide to U.S. Rep. Augustus
F. Hawkins, D-Calif. ``We want to see that the workers are taken
care of.''
   Former Lockheed President A. Carl Kotchian recalled in a recent
interview that the company's decision to open the plant four years
after the devastating riot was considered controversial.
   ``I had my own people take issue with me,'' Kotchian said.
``They said I was going to spend a lot of money and the place was
going to be run down and there was going to be thievery and
muggings at the plant. None of it came to pass.''
   Instead, the plant matched the productivity and efficiency of
most Lockheed factories, he said.
   The arrest of a black man by a state highway patrol officer on
Aug. 11, 1965, touched off a week of rioting that turned Watts into
a national symbol of racial strife.
   Thirty-four people died in the riot and 4,000 people were
arrested. Damage from the six days of looting, fires and shooting
reached $40 million.
   DV Industries, a smaller aerospace company that has operated in
Watts for 30 years, plans to take over Lockheed's 25-year lease on
the factory, which is owned by Economic Resources Corp., a
non-profit group formed after the riot.
   The company expects to double its 55-person work force over the
next year and will give hiring preference to former Lockheed
workers, said Carl La Barbera, DV's executive vice president.
   DV Industries, a privately held company with sales under $10
million per year, inspects and paints aircraft parts for Lockheed,
Boeing and other aerospace firms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
