<DOCNO> AP880709-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Politics     07-09 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Politics,0829</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Opposition Showing Marks End of PRI Monopoly, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition's strong showing in
presidential elections marks a watershed in Mexican politics _ a
transition from 59 years of a one-party system and the awakening of
a long passive electorate, political analysts say.
   Early returns indicated that Carlos Salinas de Gortari,
candidate of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, would
finish with no more than 52 percent of the vote, party officials
say. That is far below the 70 percent the party had considered the
minimum.
   The PRI has not lost a presidential, gubernatorial or senate
race since it was founded in 1929. Partial returns have shown
Salinas leading with 47.8 percent of the vote.
   PRI officials appeared willing to concede that Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas of the leftist National Democratic Front and Manuel J.
Clouthier of the conservative National Action Party would finish
better than original polls indicated.
   PRI sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, conceded
Salinas had likely lost in Michoacan, the Federal District, and
adjoining Morelos state and probably in the state of Mexico. The
Mexico City metropolitan area accounts for about 20 percent of the
38 million registered voters.
   Cardenas' and Clouthier's parties said Salinas lost, and they
claimed widespread fraud.
   The voter turnout and final results were not expected until
Sunday, but partial results were leaked in an attempt to defuse
allegations of manipulation of the vote.
   Salinas insisted on a small but credible margin of victory
rather than the frequently fraud-tainted results the party is known
for. But the almost certain loss of congressional seats and the
opposition entry into the Senate for the first time is hard for the
party's old guard.
   ``Psychologically, it means a big blow,'' Adolfo Aguilar, a
Mexican economist with the Carnegie Endowment for Peace, said.
``Politically, just imagine the slice of people they have to cut.
This chunk of votes means many PRI candidates. It's going to be
disastrous for the PRI.''
   Political analyst Jorge Castaneda said Cardenas did much better
than expected, particularly in urban areas.
   Salinas, who has said he wants to modernize Mexico, will owe his
vote ``to the poorest, most backward peasantry of the country,''
Castaneda said.
   In a victory proclamation before any results were released,
Salinas acknowledged the opposition would have more congressional
representation than in the past and said, ``The times of virtually
having a single party are over, and we now enter a new political
stage in the country's life, with a majority party and a very
intense competition by the opposition.''
   Clear-cut opposition from both the left, united for the first
time, and the right swept away decades of apathy, and voters turned
out in what officials say were record numbers.
   ``Young people turned out not just to vote but also as polling
place officials to protect the cleanliness of the election,'' Jorge
Bustamente, director of the Northern Border College in Tijuana,
said.
   ``The country is changing ... very broad sectors went to vote
even though they knew'' there would be the traditional fraud,
something that kept them away in the past, Luis Javier Garrido, a
political analyst who wrote a book on the PRI, said. ``They went to
vote for another system.''
   Lorenzo Meyer, academic director of the Colegio de Mexico, a
think tank and graduate school, said the change was long in coming.
   ``From 1940 to 1988 you can't see many political changes,'' he
said. But in the same half century, Mexico evolved from a sparsely
inhabited rural country whose people had little education to a
fast-growing urban nation with schools and well developed
communications.
   A PRI official says the answer in the Salinas administration
will be to ``play by clean rules, and on economic issues you
deliver.''
   Castaneda, reflecting a view expressed by others, said the
election ``means the end of the one-party system and also the end
of a situation where the government could do what it wanted.''
   But Garrido said he believed the PRI's assurance of a majority
in the Chamber of Deputies and Senate would keep the opposition
from influencing the government and still allow Salinas to carry
out his programs.
   ``I don't think it necessarily means more pluralism,'' he said.
He said that would come when there is the opposition's ``same right
to govern is recognized.''
   Others interviewed said Salinas would have to take the
opposition into consideration and negotiate.
   Much also will depend on the credibility of the final election
tally and the elections themselves.
   A critical factor will be whether the long-splintered left's
fragile unity for the campaign continues after the election.
Cardenas has emerged as the leader the left lacked.
   ``It's him or nobody,'' Meyer said, but he warned,
``consolidating it (the left) in a party is a formidable task.''
</TEXT>
