<DOCNO> AP880709-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1526EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RobesonChanges Bjt   07-09 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robeson Changes, Bjt,0750</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Changes In Robeson County: Are They Real Or Cosmetic?
^By ERICA JOHNSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five months after two American Indians took
hostages at a newspaper to protest local conditions, changes have
been made to address their concerns, but some say it remains to be
seen whether the reforms will bring lasting change.
   Others say the real change is that residents of Robeson County
have realized ``that they can control their lives.''
   ``It's truly cosmetic,'' Eddie Hatcher said last week of the
changes, which include a second superior court judgeship and a task
force named by Gov. Jim Martin to investigate alleged corruption in
the county.
   ``It's nothing more than to douse the fire, hoping it will go
out,'' said Hatcher, one of two Lumbee Indian men who entered the
offices of The Robesonian newspaper Feb. 1, allegedly armed, in
what they said was a protest of local corruption and discrimination
against minorities. The daylong siege ended when the governor
agreed to appoint the task force.
   The county's population of about 100,000 is 37 percent Indian,
37 percent white and 26 percent black.
   The Rev. Mac Legerton, executive director of the Center for
Community Action, also was cautious.
   ``The policy changes which have occurred relate to the
administration of the law,'' he said. ``Hopefully, these changes
will provide better treatment under the law. But they will not
ensure justice throughout Robeson County.''
   Other residents were more optimistic.
   ``From my point of view, we got the second judgeship, and we're
going to get a public defender,'' said Harvey Godwin, a Lumbee
community leader who led Julian Pierce's campaign for superior
court judge.
   ``That's pretty good,'' Godwin said. ``But we're making sure
that people don't forget and don't let up. We're taking care of
business.''
   Pierce, a Lumbee who was running against District Attorney Joe
Freeman Britt for Robeson County's superior court judgeship, was
shot to death in March in what initially was called an
assassination but was later termed a domestic dispute. That left
the post to Britt, who has sent more people to death row than any
other prosecutor in the nation.
   After it became apparent that the judgeship would go to Britt,
the state agreed to create a second judgeship, which would go to a
member of a minority group.
   Hatcher said the second judgeship ``was just to appease the
people of Robeson County, hoping that the people will die down.''
   Because Britt is expected to be the county's senior judge, he
``will be able to set the (judicial) calendar, pick a magistrate,
and set the bail-bond policy,'' Hatcher said. ``What have we
gained? Nothing.''
   But Hatcher said real change has come in the minds of Lumbee
Indians and blacks.
   ``The people have seen changes in themselves because they have
realized that they can control their lives,'' he said.
   ``Now it's not just me and (fellow accused hostage-taker Timothy
Jacobs) speaking out,'' Hatcher said. ``Now it's the poor farmer,
it's the grass-roots people. They're realizing they can do
something. They're unaccustomed to politically fighting back. But
they're beginning to.''
   He cited a referendum vote to unite the county's five-school
system that passed by a razor-thin margin this spring. Supporters
say it will lessen economic and educational disparities among
schools in the system and foster a sense of common purpose.
   Godwin agreed that many people in Robeson County who previously
have felt powerless now feel differently.
   ``People are angry, but the point is, they realize that they can
do something about it,'' he said. ``I think people are going to
take advantage of that, especially the younger people.''
   ``It used to be we were just lost,'' said Georgeanna Chavis, 66.
``Now, it seems that we are coming out.''
   Mrs. Chavis also said she thought whites have treated her better
in recent months.
   ``Maybe they feel that we're trying to pull ourselves out of
where we were,'' she said. ``It's like white people are saying `We
don't see why they waited so long.'''
   Would those changes have come about without the protest Hatcher
and Jacobs staged?
   ``I think they certainly can be given credit,'' said the Rev.
Joy Johnson, a leader of Concerned Citizens and vice-chairman of
the county's human-relations commission. ``We don't approve of
their means. But I think they gave us the impetus for change in
Robeson County.''
</TEXT>
