<HEAD>Ex-Regional Counsel Charged</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chief attorney of the U.S.
Postal Service for the Western region has been charged with four
counts of battery or abusive sexual contact against female
employees.
   Lyman Johnston, 62, a 21-year employee of the Postal Service,
was indicted by a federal grand jury on four charges, two of them
felonies, U.S. Attorney Joseph Russoniello said Friday. The maximum
punishment is nine years in prison.
   All of the incidents took place at the regional headquarters in
San Bruno, south of San Francisco, between June 1985 and last
December, the grand jury said.
   Johnston, whose title was regional counsel, was notified in
February that he would be removed from his job, but was allowed to
retire voluntarily in April, Russoniello said.
