<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan     07-09 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nationalists Turning To Younger Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Nationalist Party began
Saturday to partially dismantle its old-guard leadership, but it
has yet to decide how much new blood to inject into its top ranks.
   The party removed 10 of the 31 members of the policy-making
Central Standing Committee, including five who are in their 80s.
The 10 were named to the Central Advisory Committee, an honorary
supervisory group of mostly retired officials.
   Nationalist leaders have stressed the importance of promoting
younger members of the party, known as the Kuomingtang, which was
formed 94 years ago on the Chinese mainland and has for four
decades claimed to be the sole rightful ruler of China.
   Party spokesman Raymond Tai told reporters that the new Central
Standing Committee will be named Thursday at the end of the
weeklong 13th party congress. A Cabinet overhaul is expected later.
   Most of the aging leaders in the current Central Standing
Committee _ whose members' average age is 70 _ fled to Taiwan from
the Chinese mainland in 1949, when Chiang Kai-shek and his
Nationalist government were routed by the Communists.
   These older Nationalists still hold a majority of seats in the
Parliament and support the party's claim that it has the right to
govern China.
   The personnel changes are likely to determine the pace for
continuing the liberalization program started by President Chiang
Ching-kuo before his death in January. Chiang, the eldest son of
Chiang Kai-shek, lifted martial law, allowed new political parties
and eased a ban on travel to mainland China.
   President Lee Teng-hui, who Friday was elected the first native
Taiwanese party chairman, has vowed to continue the democratic
changes, but he has moved cautiously in the past months in order to
consolidate his power.
   The new members of the advisory committee were proposed by Lee
and approved by the party congress.
   Three media executives on the Central Standing Committee who
have said they want to give way to a younger leadership also were
named to the advisory panel.
   But two influential 74-year-old conservatives on the
policy-making committee _ Premier Yu Kuo-hwa and Shen Chang-huan,
secretary to the president _were not reassigned.
   The Independence Evening Post newspaper said Saturday that Yu
and four other elder statesmen will remain a major force as ``the
old generals lead the team while the young officials intern.''
   ``This will be a very conservative restructuring,'' wrote
political commentator Antonio Chiang. He added that as the older
politicians' power base diminishes, younger members of the party
may be more willing to speak out.
   The 1,209 delegates to the party congress will elect a
180-member Central Committee on Tuesday. For the first time, the
vote will not be limited to candidates proposed by the party.
   Discussions among congress delegates on topics ranging from
agriculture to China reportedly became heated Saturday.
   ``The atmosphere of this congress is different'' from previous
ones, said spokesman Tai. ``There was serious debate and
discussions, and delegates made candid suggestions to party
leaders.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880709-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BoysNightOut     07-09 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boys Night Out,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Invites Capitol Hill Storytellers For Evening Of `Yarn
Swapping'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the first lady out of town and the
president looking for a good time, invitations went out to some of
the best storytellers on Capitol Hill for an evening of ``yarn
swapping'' at the White House.
   ``He just wanted to have the boys come in, have dinner, and have
a bull session,'' Alabama Sen. Howell Heflin said Saturday. ``Most
of it was just levity and jokes. It was just sort of a night out
with the boys.''
   Mrs. Reagan was in New York to meet with her publisher, Random
House, about plans to write her memoirs.
   Democrat Heflin was one of six legislators who shared their best
stories with President Reagan during a four-hour session Friday
night in the president's private quarters at the White House.
   And what were some of those best stories?
   ``That's one thing there's a pledge of secrecy on,'' Heflin
said. ``At least on the stories he might have told, anyway. ...
There were a lot of good ones, but they're all super secret.''
   Heflin said he told Reagan his story about ``expectations,''
where the elderly lady, after striking up a conversation on an
airplane with an elderly gentleman, pats him on the knee and tells
him he reminds her of her third husband.
   ``The man said, `Oh, is that right. And how many times have you
been married?' And she replied, `twice,''' Heflin said.
   The evening's conversation drifted into serious discussion only
rarely, according to Heflin. Once was when Rep. Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., asked Reagan what he would most like to see his successor
accomplish.
   ``He said he would like to see him push forward and adopt a
constitutional amendment to balance the budget and also to get a
line item veto,'' Heflin said. ``And then we discussed those
aspects of fiscal responsibility.''
   On another occasion, Heflin said, Reagan told the group about
some of his discussions with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
during the Moscow summit in May.
   Reagan also talked at length about his early days in the movies,
Heflin said, and at one point he described all the ``considerations
and ethics boards and everything'' that had to be cleared before
Rhett Butler, played by Clark Gable, could use the word ``damn'' in
the closing scene of ``Gone With The Wind.''
   ``He was in effect decrying the ways movies have changed,''
Heflin said. ``He talked about how the movies used to have a power
of suggestion that the mind worked on and now there is so much
activity that it leaves nothing for the mind to imagine.''
   In addition to Heflin and Rostenkowski, others invited to the
Friday evening session with the president were Sen. Alan Simpson,
R-Wyo., Rep. Robert Michel, R-Ill., Rep. Gene Taylor, R-Mo., Rep.
Marvin Leath, D-Texas, and Kenneth Duberstein, the White House
chief of staff.
</TEXT>
