<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OilRig-Victims     07-09 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig-Victims,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>List of Dead Reveals Private Disasters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Oil-Rig Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The list of dead in the disaster on
the Piper Alpha oil platform is an index of 166 private disasters.
   A bride of a few weeks became a widow. A man died because he
volunteered to return to work a week early. A 19-year-old who had
worked offshore only a few days perished in the explosion and fire
120 miles east of Scotland in the North Sea.
   Alice Williamson, a 25-year-old nurse, was settling into married
life in Aberdeen when her 24-year-old husband Paul returned to
Piper Alpha on Wednesday, the day it exploded.
   She waited 24 hours for her worst fears to be confirmed.
``Something inside me told me he wouldn't be coming back,'' she
said Saturday. ``I just knew.''
   Rig worker David Henderson, 28, would have returned returned
home Monday, the day before his wife Margaret expects to give birth.
   Safety officer Cyril Gray, 49, was to begin vacation Tuesday and
telephoned his wife two hours before the explosion.
   ``He phoned every night,'' Mrs. Gray said. ``He said he would
phone me the next day and then said he loved me.''
   Offshore production manager Donald Reid arrived on Piper Alpha
only hours before the explosion.
   Mark Ashton, 19, was a trainee technician who started working
offshore just a few days before.
   ``He ... was very enthusiastic about his new job,'' said
Ashton's 16-year-old brother Jonathan. ``He was really looking
forward to going offshore last Saturday.''
   William McGregor, 48, volunteered to return to work a week
early. He had been planning to marry in a few weeks.
   The platform's entire catering crew of 18 was killed. They
arrived on Piper Alpha a week earlier when their employers, Kelvin
Catering, took over the food contract.
   Engineer John Cooper, 37, was telephoning his mother to tell her
he would be home on leave the following day when Piper Alpha blew
up, she said.
   Cooper told his mother, Harriet: ``Just a minute, I think
there's been an explosion,'' then the line went dead.
   Two girls, aged 9 and 10 could not accept that their father, oil
rigger Harold Green, would never come home again and they are under
sedation.
   Green's wife, Lesley, said: ``I think they think he is only hurt
and that he's still going to come home.''
   Tony Sinnett survived and said his workmate, rigging foreman
Tommy Hayes, 39, was a hero.
   Sinnett said Hayes took breathing equipment from the platform's
reception area and urged men sheltering in the crew's quarters to
leave the rig. He said Hayes saved as many as 17 lives but the time
it took cost his own.
   Hayes had a wife, Lynda, and two teen-age children.
   The brother of one victim watched from another platform as
flames engulfed the Piper Alpha.
   Keith Ellis was on a rig 20 miles away, watching the Piper Alpha
burn with his brother David on board.
   ``We could see the blaze clearly and I couldn't take my eyes off
it for 12 hours,'' he said.
</TEXT>
