<HEAD>Thief Held at Gunpoint by Judge Gets Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who took a child's playhouse from a
judge's home and was later tracked down, held at gunpoint and
handcuffed by the judge has been sentenced to 15 years in prison.
   Jimmy Garcia, 17, also had his probation revoked Friday by
Wallace Moore, visiting state district judge. Garcia had been on
probation for burglary.
   Moore also complimented Harris County Judge Al Leal, who handles
misdemeanor cases and caught Garcia.
   ``I wish you'd come to my neighborhood,'' Moore told Leal.
   Leal spotted Garcia and another man stealing a children's
playhouse at Leals' home on April 25, a day after the judge's car
was burglarized.
   On April 27, after receiving information that the missing
playhouse was at a nearby apartment complex, Leal flagged down a
policeman and led him on a search for his missing property.
   Leal saw Garcia on a bicycle and accosted the youth. The judge
pulled a gun on the teen-ager and put handcuffs on him.
   Prosecutor Jules Laird said Leal was fully within his rights to
carry a gun and function as a policeman.
