<DOCNO> AP880709-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1648EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Insurance     07-09 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Insurance,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Threatens To Revoke Insurance Company's License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An insurance company faces revocation of
its license in Minnesota if it refuses to issue drought-insurance
policies to about 1,000 farmers who paid for more than $40 million
in coverage, a state official says.
   Minnesota Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch said Friday that
New Jersey-based Chubb Insurance Cos. informed farmers who paid for
the policies by a June 15 deadline that the policies will not be
issued.
   But under a 1987 state law, once an insurance agent accepts and
cashes a check from a farmer, the policy cannot be canceled by
either party, Hatch said. All checks were cashed by June 15, Hatch
said.
   ``We've told the company that we want the policies issued,''
Hatch said. ``We're saying if you don't issue the policies, we'll
ask the attorney general's office to prepare documents to revoke''
the company's license to do business in Minnesota.
   Hatch said a meeting is scheduled Monday between state officials
and company representatives.
   Company officials did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
   Chubb had told Minnesota insurance agents that the sales should
be canceled and premiums refunded to buyers, Hatch said. The
company explained that sales exceeded its capacity.
   Hatch said Chubb was remiss for deciding halfway through a
drought-stricken summer to refund premiums on drought coverage.
   When the issue first arose last week, Chubb contended that it
had taken applications that didn't translate into coverage until it
approved them. Some of the applications contain such a statement
and others don't, Hatch said.
   The insurance would begin paying buyers a percentage of the full
amount if rainfall fell below 70 percent of normal at the nearest
official rain gauge during June, July and August. The lower the
rainfall, the higher the amount paid.
</TEXT>
