<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OperationCrackdown     07-09 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Operation Crackdown,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Police Slam `Operation Crackdown' As Media Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of television and print
reporters tagged along as Broward Sheriff's deputies busted 107
drug suspects and swung sledgehammers to demolish five abandoned
houses frequented by crack dealers.
   The activities Friday were part of ``Operation Crackdown,'' the
third sweep this year conducted by the sheriff's office for the
media to watch. Some of the arrests were sting operations, in which
deputies posed as drug dealers.
   ``The media draw attention to it,'' said sheriff's spokesman Al
Gordon. ``We want people to know that when they buy drugs in
Broward County, they may be buying from a deputy. And they're going
to jail.''
   Also taking part in the arrests were officers from Margate,
North Lauderdale and Pompano Beach police agenices. But not all
area police forces like the idea.
   ``An arrest is an arrest is an arrest whether or not it's on the
6 o'clock news,'' said Hollywood Police Chief Richard Witt,
describing Broward Sheriff Nick Navarro as ``a media mogul.''
   ``When we conduct street-level operations, to us, the media gets
in the way,'' said Fort Lauderdale Police Chief Joe Gerwens. ``I
think narcotics operations are complicated enough without dragging
the media along.
   ``We don't operate that way. We turned away Geraldo (Rivera, the
television talk show host) ... on two occasions,'' Gerwens said.
   Rivera in September 1986 took part in a similar sweep by the
Broward Sheriff's Office.
   The television personality posed as the financier in the
undercover sting, and used videotape of it for his television
special, ``American Vice: The Doping of a Nation,'' broadcast
months later.
   In Friday's sweep, besides demolitions and the arrests,
Operation Crackdown netted 10 guns from one home, had 40 cars towed
from in front of vacant houses, and small amounts of crack and
marijuana, said spokesman Gordon. Crack is a form of cocaine that's
smoked.
   Among those arrested was former Pompano Beach policeman James
Evans, who was charged with trying to buy cocaine from an
undercover officer.
</TEXT>
