<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-09 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Scorcher For The Ohio And Tennessee Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was widely scattered over the eastern two-thirds of the
nation Saturday, and extreme heat returned to the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys with more record temperatures.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed along a cold front crossing
the north-central states, and a severe thunderstorm watch was
posted for sections of northern and central Minnesota, northeastern
South Dakota and a small part of southeastern North Dakota.
   Showers and thunderstorms were fairly numerous from northwestern
Oklahoma through the eastern half of Nebraska to southwestern
Wisconsin.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed across western Texas,
along the central Gulf Coast, across southern and central Florida,
in the middle Atlantic Coast region; and in New England,
particularly in northern Maine.
   Atlantic, N.J., got 1.62 inches of rain in the six hours up to 2
p.m. EDT.
   Showers prevailed in the southern and central Rockies.
   Temperatures soared above 100 degrees across parts of Tennessee,
Kentucky, Indiana and Ohio.
   Record highs included 95 at Binghamton, N.Y.; 100 at Huntington,
W.Va.; 102 at Louisville, Ky.; 100 at Knoxville, Tenn.; 94 at
Mansfield, Ohio; 101 at Nashville, Tenn.; and 99 at Roanoke, Va.
   Buffalo, N.Y., tied its record for the date of 92, marking a
record six days in a row of 90 or higher heat. As far north as
Maine, Portland tied its record of 92.
   On the other hand, Jacksonville, Fla., had a record low of 66
degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 61
degrees at Hoquiam, Wash., to 110 at Needles and Palm Springs,
Calif. The early morning low for the day was 33 degrees at Jackson,
Wyo.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
across much of the area from the Rocky Mountains to the Atlantic
Coast, expecially in the upper Great Lakes and Florida.
   Highs only in the 70s were predicted from North Dakota to Upper
Michigan, and along the Pacific Coast; above 90 in much of the area
from the southern Plains to the Atlantic Coast states; and above
100 in the Tennessee Valley, the lower Ohio Valley and the desert
Southwest, where some readings will approach 115. Elsewhere,
temperatures will generally be in the 80s.
</TEXT>
