<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0576 07-09 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0576,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Killed In Clash; Strike Shuts Down Commerce</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with 9 grafs to CORRECT that one wounded by gunfire and
another injured by explosive in Jebalya, sted two shot and wounded.
Pickup 7th graf pvs ``The army...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers and Palestinian protesters
clashed in street battles across the occupied territories Saturday.
One Palestinian was fatally shot, raising the death toll to 217 as
the uprising against Israeli rule entered its eighth month.
   A general strike shut down commerce in major cities and towns.
   Palestinian reports said at least 34 protesters were injured.
The army put the figure at 11.
   Palestinian reporters said soldiers fatally shot 25-year-old
Fayek Suleiman Hussein in the heart after opening fire on
stone-throwing protesters in Jebalya refugee camp in the occupied
Gaza Strip. Hospital officials said two people were injured.
   The army confirmed the death in Jebalya but said it was
investigating the circumstances.
   Officials at Shifa Hospital in Gaza said a woman, Suad Dib
Ippbail, 34, was wounded in the hand by gunfire during the clash in
Jebalaya.
   A five-year-old boy, Samir Mahmud Zidan, also suffered wounds in
the face, left hand and left leg when he played with an explosive
during or after the clash, the officials said. It was not
immediately known what kind of explosive was involved.
   Palestinian reporters said earlier that both people injured in
Jebalya were wounded by gunfire.
   In Arura, near the West Bank city of Ramallah, witnesses said
soldiers beat five demonstrators during a raid and fractured a
man's skull by knocking his head against a wall and beating it with
a rifle butt.
   The army said troops detained several stone-throwing youths in
Arura after chasing them into homes. It said it was investigating
charges of excessive force.
   Stores were closed and public transportation was halted in Arab
East Jerusalem, Ramallah, Nablus, Hebron, Gaza City and other main
towns in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The shutdowns, expected to last at least through Sunday, follow
the instructions of a leaflet signed by the ``Unified National
Leadership of the Uprising-the PLO.''
   In some cities, such as Nablus, the strike began Friday under
orders contained in different leaflets apparently issued by a rival
underground faction.
   The strikes signified the start of the eighth month of the
uprising, which began Dec. 8. According to official figures, 217
Arabs have been killed. Four Israelis have died.
   Clashes broke out in half a dozen towns and refugee camps in the
occupied territories.
   In Arura, a village of 3,000, Arabs hurled blocks and bottles at
soldiers, the army said, after soldiers apparently entered the area
after midnight to conduct arrests.
   One soldier received medical treatment after being struck in the
shoulder by a block, and then the troops chased the stone-throwers
into homes and detained several of them hiding under beds, an army
spokesman said.
   During the ensuing raid, soldiers broke furniture and windows in
at least 10 homes and beat five villagers with sticks and rifle
butts, said Joost Hiltermann, a spokesman for Law in the Service of
Man, the West Bank affiliate of the Geneva-based International
Commission of Jurists.
   Hassan Abdel Rahman, 23, was in intensive care at nearby
Ramallah Hospital with a fractured skull after being beaten with a
rifle butt and having his head smashed into a wall, hospital
officials said.
   The army confirmed three Palestinians were injured and
hospitalized after soldiers used ``reasonable force'' to try to
detain them. It said it would investigate complaints about the
beatings and vandalism.
   In a clash at the Khan Yunis refugee camp in Gaza, soldiers
opened fire on stone-throwers who surrounded the troops, wounding
17-year-old Mohammed Abu Silmiya in the leg, the army said.
   Palestinian reports said 17 people were treated for tear gas and
beating injuries after the incident.
   Also in Gaza, a Palestinian reporter said a 22-year-old man,
Shawki Mohammed Khalil Odeh, was hospitalized and his right eye
swollen shut after soldiers beat him in the head and kicked him
after a stoning attack on troops.
   The army said soldiers imposed curfews on four refugee camps in
Gaza and closed the West Bank's largest city of Nablus to
reporters, declaring it a closed military zone.
   Soldiers fought for 90 minutes with protesters in Bani Naim near
Hebron, and three protesters were injured by rubber bullets, Arab
reports said.
   The army said six demonstrators were injured by rubber bullets
in the Aida refugee camp near Bethlehem after soldiers fired on
several Palestinians who tried to grab a gun from a soldier and
stoned the troops.
</TEXT>
