<2ND_LINE>AM-Rooming House Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0616,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Die In Old Rooming House As Fires Flare</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with fire investigator at
scene, further comment on possibility of arson, condition of
injured man, other detail, and to fix grammar in lead. No pickup.
Stands for story slugged AM-Hotel Fire on AM-News Advisory</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PASCO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire quickly engulfed an old, wood-frame
rooming house early Saturday, killing three people and seriously
burning another, and a rash of smaller fires was reported across
the city.
   Fire Chief Larry Dickinson said firefighters were kept busy
going from fire to fire as flames broke out in 10 separate places
in garbage bins, brush along fence lines and in an apartment
building 20 blocks from the destroyed rooming house. Only minor
damage was reported in those fires.
   John Fifer, assistant fire chief in this south-central
Washington town of 18,000, said a state fire marshal had been
called in to determine whether the fatal fire was linked to the
others, which he said were probably arson.
   ``We are presuming those (others) are all set fires,'' he said.
There have been no arrests, officials said.
   The state investigator was on the scene Saturday afternoon, said
firefighter Dennis Morris. But he and others said they did not want
to be too quick to label the fatal fire as arson before they had
ruled out other possible causes.
   ``You can always say arson, but that is a pretty easy way out,''
Morris said.
   The dead were tentatively identified, but authorities were
withholding their names pending positive identification and
notification of relatives. All three victims were males, Fifer said.
   The manager of the destroyed building, Godfrey Davis, said he
discovered the fire at 3:45 a.m. as he got up to go to work.
   ``When I opened the door, it seemed like all hell was busting
loose,'' Davis said. ``It knocked me back. So then I started
hollering, `Get everybody out there! It's a fire!'''
   One of the victims was a double amputee who called down the
stairs from the second floor that he couldn't find his artificial
legs in the smoke, Davis said. He said he told the frightened man
to jump, but he wouldn't.
   Morris said the rubble from the rooming house was searched and
no other victims were found. There were reportedly 20 to 25 people
in the two-story building when the fire hit.
   Davis said it seemed to him that the fire had begun outside the
building, but fire officials said they had not determined where it
began.
   The fires at the apartment building 20 blocks away were set in a
garbage can and a laundry room, but were quickly extinguished, said
fire officials.
   The burned man was taken to Our Lady of Lourdes Health Center
and later transferred to Harborview Medical Center in Seattle, said
Lourdes nursing supervisor Peggy Tschauner. She identified him as
Steven Knight, 32.
   At Harborview, Knight was listed in serious condition with
second and third-degree burns over 30 percent of his body.
   The Red Cross was handing out food and blankets to those left
homeless by the blaze.
   The first fire was reported in a garbage bin, and the second to
be reported was the fatal fire, Fifer said. The other eight fires
were discovered later.
   ``While we were fighting the fire at this location (the rooming
house), we had a couple of engines as a task force going from one
fire to another ... handling those (smaller) fires,'' Fifer said.
</TEXT>
