<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 1812EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OilRig-NATOShips     07-09 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig-NATO Ships,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Ships Ready to Help, But Too Late</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Rig, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTSMOUTH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO sailors who were diverted from
their maneuvers in the North Sea to help search for victims of the
Piper Alpha oil platform disaster said Saturday it caused in them
the dread all seamen have of fire.
   ``When you have been at sea, you know you are always one step
away from a disaster like that,'' said Rear Adm. John Scott Redd of
the U.S. Navy, who commands the alliance's Standing Naval Force
Atlantic.
   ``You live with that. Whenever it happens there is a desire to
come to the assistance of those in trouble on the sea,'' he said.
   Redd said conditions were excellent in the normally brutal North
Sea as the six NATO ships approached the burning wreckage, with
good visibility and relatively calm waters.
   ``We had all the conditions required to find survivors, had
there been any,'' he said. ``If you looked anywhere except where
the platform was burning, it was a nice, pleasant day.''
   The scene around the Piper Alpha was different, however.
   ``It quickly became apparent what an awful tragedy had occurred
when you saw things like a burned-out lifeboat, bits of furniture
and floating debris from the platform,'' he said.
   Redd spoke to reporters after the NATO warships involved in the
search returned to Portsmouth, 65 miles southwest of London.
   Cmdr. Alan Phillips of the Royal Navy said his ship, HMS Phoebe,
sometimes was only 400 yards from the platform, which exploded and
burned Wednesday night with the loss of 166 lives.
   ``You could hardly see the rig,'' he said. ``it was engulfed in
flames. It brought home the fear any mariner has of fire at sea.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
