<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     07-09 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Ministry Reports Two Rebel Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry said U.S.-backed
rebels twice attacked troops Saturday in violation of a
government-declared cease-fire, killing two soldiers in one attack
and losing four dead in another.
   The ministry said in a statement that the rebels, known as
Contras, killed two soldiers, wounded one and captured four others
in a morning ambush about 90 miles northeast of Managua in the
province of Matagalpa.
   In another incident in a remote region near the Caribbean coast,
four rebels were killed when they attacked Sandinista troops, the
statement said.
   The government has declared a unilateral cease-fire until July
31 to allow time to restart stalled peace talks.
   A fragile truce has been in effect since March 21, but no new
sessions of talks have been scheduled to end the nearly 7-year-old
war between the Contras and the leftist Sandinista regime.
   The Contras agreed to go along with the latest cease-fire as
long as they weren't attacked. Saturday's Defense Ministry
statement was the latest in a series of government charges that the
rebels are ignoring the truce.
   It said Defense Minister Humberto Ortega has asked a monitoring
commission set up after the first round of talks to verify a rebel
attack July 4 in the Chontales province. The government says 12
soldiers and civilians were killed in that attack.
   The Sandinistas came to power in July 1979 after 42 years of
rule by the rightist, pro-U.S. government of Anastasio Somoza.
</TEXT>
