<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TigerAttack     07-09 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tiger Attack,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman in Critical Condition After Tiger Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOTHELL, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was critically injured when a
tiger attacked her after she fell during a filming session for the
Boeing Co. at a wild game farm, authorities said.
   Clara Frobig, 40, was listed in critical condition Saturday at
Evergreen Hospital in Kirkland following surgery for severe wounds
to the head, neck and shoulder.
   The owner of Animal Advocates wild game farm, Anne Gordon, said
Ms. Frobig had been working as a volunteer about a month.
   Boeing needed footage of a tiger running through tall grass. The
tiger, named Sultan, was to be unleashed by an assistant and run to
Ms. Gordon, who was holding food, for the filming. Volunteers held
portable fencing to help corral the animal.
   After a successful dry run, the tiger began his lope, then
veered toward the fence that Ms. Frobig was holding, Ms. Gordon
said. Ms. Frobig moved to readjust the fence but fell in the bumpy
grass.
   ``When she fell down, the tiger was thinking, `Oh, this is a fun
toy.' When he did bite, he became possessive and didn't want anyone
to take her away. He carried her about 10 feet,'' Ms. Gordon said.
   She said one assistant hit the tiger with a heavy stick and
another dove onto the animal, trying to get him to let go. After
the tiger backed off, Ms. Gordon calmed it down and took it back to
its cage.
   Sultan, a 3-year-old, 500-pound Bengal tiger, remained in
quarantine at Animal Advocates. Ms. Gordon said she had owned him
since he was 3 weeks old, and he never attacked anyone before.
   Ms. Gordon, 30, a former zookeeper in Seattle, said she had
operated the farm as a non-profit organization for five years,
mostly to raise and train animals and take them to schools to teach
children about wildlife. She said she would now close the farm.
   It was animals from Animal Advocates that starred in the movie
``Harry and the Hendersons,'' Ms. Gordon said.
</TEXT>
