<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     07-09 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims New Heights Liberated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its forces recaptured a series
of mountain peaks in its northern Kurdistan mountains Saturday
after a four-day battle with Iranian forces.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, Cyprus,
said numerous areas along the northern front were taken back,
including 14 mountain peaks.
   It also said Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery shot down an Iranian
F-4 jet fighter as it attempted to cross into Iraqi territory.
   A report carried by Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency
denied losing any planes Saturday. IRNA, also monitored in Nicosia,
confirmed there was fighting in the northern mountains.
   In the last three months, the Iraqis have achieved important
victories including the recapture of an oil terminal at Faw in
April, the Salamcheh region in May and the southern oil-rich
Majnoon marshes in June.
   After its victories in the south, Iraq has been concentrating on
driving Iranian forces out of its the northern mountains. Previous
Iraqi communiques have claimed the Iranians were dislodged from
their last mountain strongholds, but the fighting has apparently
continued.
   In another development Saturday, Iran's acting
commander-in-chief Hashemi Rafsanjani met with Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini's designated heir to discuss strengthening the war effort,
Tehran radio reported.
   Rafsanjani and Ayatollah Hussein Ali Montazeri met at
Montazeri's home in the holy city of Qom, 100 miles south of Tehran.
   Montazeri has said Iran's Revolutionary Guards should be merged
with the regular army to streamline the chain of command.
Rafsanjani favors a joint command but has argued against merging
the two formations.
   The guards are a major power base for Rafsanjani.
   There have been sharp differences in Iran's religious hierarchy
over the military formations, especially after recent defeats in
the nearly 8-year-old conflict with Iraq.
   Rafsanjani was appointed acting commander-in-chief by Khomeini
on June 2.
</TEXT>
