<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0626,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush Plan To Boost Fees Is Tax Increase</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``I understand
...'' to UPDATE with Jackson comments; SUBS 20th graf, bgng:
``Dukakis was ...'' to delete first reference to Jackson.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said Saturday a plan
by George Bush to boost fees for some government services amounts
to raising taxes, something the Republican vice president has said
he would not do.
   ``I understand yesterday he had some difficulty distinguishing
between certain kinds of taxes and other taxes,'' Dukakis said.
``Back where I come from, if it looks like a duck and walks like a
duck and quacks like a duck, it's a duck.''
   Jesse Jackson, as he attended a private fund-raiser in Los
Angeles, denied reports he and his delegates might stage a walkout
at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   ``The threat is not that we're going to walk out,'' he told
reporters. ``The threat is that we're going to stay and expand and
build and grow and make a difference.''
   He gave no sign of surrendering to the Dukakis camp, saying,
``my name will be in nomination. We will have (platform) planks on
the floor, those that are not resolved between now and that time,
and that should be a reasonable expectation.''
   Dukakis was referring to comments by the vice president that he
favors higher fees including higher payments for Medicare
recipients who choose to accept catastrophic health care coverage
under terms of recent health legislation.
   ``I don't know if Mr. Bush has problems trying to distinguish
between taxes and premiums, but I think we'd better read the fine
print in that insurance policy very, very carefully before we sign
on,'' Dukakis said in opening remarks at a news conference.
   Republicans, meanwhile, holding a rally in Atlanta, attacked
Dukakis on his search for a running mate, his fiscal policies and
his size.
   Lee Atwater, national campaign manager for Bush, said Dukakis'
search for a vice presidential candidate to join him on the ticket
was ``making Hamlet look like the rock of Gibraltar.''
   Atwater also said the Massachusetts governor's decision to raise
taxes in his home state while running for president was ``dumb.''
   ``If you're undertaxed, vote for Dukakis. If you're overtaxed
... we want you in our party,'' said Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., a
former candidate himself for the GOP presidential nomination.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., and Florida Gov. Bob Martinez made
cracks about Dukakis' height.
   Thurmond called Dukakis ``a mere midget compared to George
Bush.''
   Martinez said the differences in experience between Bush and
Dukakis amounted to ``the tale of the tall and the short.''
   Dukakis is 5 feet 8 inches tall.
   Dukakis spoke to a group of about 250 students at the Evans
Community Adult School, a public school for immigrants in downtown
Los Angeles.
   Dukakis reminded them of his own immigrant heritage and said to
them, ``You are the future of this country.''
   Dukakis, who will pick up the Democratic presidential nomination
next week in Atlanta, again found himself faced with repeated
questioning on his continuing deliberations about the vice
presidential candidate.
   He said he had not made a decision, did not know when he would
announce one and would meet with senior aide Paul Brountas after
returning to Boston Sunday to discuss the choice.
   At a later appearance in Portland, Ore., Dukakis toured a Navy
ship being refitted at the port shipyard and spoke to a small
crowd. He cited the investigation into alleged fraud on Pentagon
weapons contracts and blasted the Reagan administration, saying it
``not only doesn't believe in public service, it's contemptuous of
public service.''
   ``I don't know what the true nature is of this breaking scandal
over the Pentagon. I don't take any particular pleasure in it _ I
think it's a very sad day,'' Dukakis said. ``But I'll tell you this
_ I'm going to do everything I can as president of the United
States to stop that revolving door'' between the Pentagon and
defense contractors that often hire former military officials.
   Dukakis was flying on to Tacoma, Wash., for a tour of the port
on a tugboat. He was ending the day in the Rocky Mountains at Estes
Park, Colo.
   Dukakis was accompanied throughout his California stop by Sen.
Alan Cranston, who sat with him at a Los Angeles Dodgers baseball
game Friday night. Cranston said he believed Sen. John Glenn of
Ohio remained the most likely vice presidential choice and that
Tennessee Sen. Albert J. Gore Jr. would pose a problem if selected
because he did not run as well in the presidential race as did
Jackson.
   ``I kind of doubt that it will be somebody who ran,'' Cranston
said. ``Unless they pick No. 2, and that's Jesse Jackson, it's a
little awkward to go to somebody who ran third, fourth, fifth,
sixth or seventh.''
   Shortly after arriving in California, Dukakis was asked if he
was consulting with Jackson on the selection of a running mate.
   ``Am I consulting him? No,'' Dukakis said.``We're talking, and
he's one of a number of people I'm considering. As he himself has
said, it's up to the nominee, and I'll make that decision.''
</TEXT>
