<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PeaceConvoy     07-09 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Convoy,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua-Bound Activists Arrested at International Bridge During
Scuffle</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LAR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAREDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight members of a convoy carrying aid to
Nicaraguan civilians were arrested Saturday during a melee after
they tried to cross a bridge into Mexico.
   The scuffle broke out on the international bridge when officers
sprayed a cayenne-based irritant into the truck of the Veterans
Peace Convoy, which had blocked a traffic lane for four hours.
   Police arrested the eight as 50 of their supporters chanted,
``The whole world is watching!'' and rushed past a line of police
at the bridge toll booth that separates the United States from
Mexico.
   Customs officers said allowing the trucks to leave the United
States without assurances they would be returned would violate a
trade embargo against Nicaragua.
   The convoy, which had tried to cross the same bridge a month
ago, had intended to take 17 vehicles into Mexico at noon Saturday.
Two trucks were driven to the toll booth where Customs officers and
police stopped them.
   Frank Zapata, acting chief Customs inspector, told Bob Livesey,
driver of the convoy's lead pickup, that he could not allow him to
turn onto the Mexico-bound lane.
   ``This is as far as you're going to get,'' Zapata told Livesey.
``You can turn north (back to Texas) here if you want.''
   Livesey responded: ``We're not moving. ... We're either going to
Nicaragua through Mexico here _ this is a free border _ or we're
going to jail.'' He then placed several boxes of baby food on the
hood of his car and refused to budge.
   Four hours later, police again told the trucks' occupants they
must move the vehicles or be arrested. The trucks stayed put, and
officers stuck a nightstick into a window of a truck driven by
Harry Meserve, 45, of Santa Cruz, Calif. The window shattered as
Meserve tried to roll it up. Officers simultaneously sprayed the
cab with the substance laced with cayenne, a very hot, irritating
spice.
   About 50 supporters of the convoy had been watching and rushed
past officers as the arrests began. Some started pounding on a
convoy truck, shouting, ``The whole world is watching!''
   Livesey, 46, a Vietnam veteran from Massachusetts, and Meserve
were among those arrested.
   ``There was a little bit of pushing and shoving but there was
nothing where anybody was in any real, serious danger,'' said
Police Chief Victor Garcia. Once the arrests were made, the crowd
began following officers' orders and moved back, he said.
   Police towed the convoy's pickup trucks off the bridge, and
traffic across it was restored to normal soon afterward.
</TEXT>
