<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Iranians,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians In London Protest Airliner Shootdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Iranian children carrying a large paper
airplane splattered with red paint led about 600 other Iranians
past the U.S. Embassy on Saturday to protest the U.S. downing of an
Iranian airliner in the Persian Gulf.
   Marchers shook clenched fists as they passed the embassy in
central London's Grosvenor Square and shouted repeatedly, ``Down
with U.S.A.!''
   Some held banners demanding the withdrawal of U.S. warships from
the Persian Gulf. Others carried life-size photographs of Iranian
leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Before the marchers started out from Marble Arch in central
London, they said prayers for the victims of the incident July 3 in
which Iran says 290 people died.
   The United States said the warship that shot down the plane
mistook the aircraft for a hostile Iranian fighter jet.
   The march was organized by Iranian students. Scotland Yard, the
London police headquarters, said there were no disturbances and no
arrests were made.
