<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Argentina-Election 1stLd-Writethru a0650gthscoreoverRunTheTableandfavoridtwoandthrewthreewildpitches.BarryLarkinwalked
07-09 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Menem Posts Upset Victory Over Cafiero In Peronist Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with latest nationwide returns,
Cafiero conceding, Menem quotes, details. Picks up 7th graf pvs
``In a related...''; DROPS 11th graf pvs ``While both...'' to
CONFORM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peronist Party's first
presidential primary in four decades Saturday gave La Rioja
provincial Gov. Carlos Menem an upset victory over Buenos Aires
provincial Gov. Antonio Cafiero, officials said.
   Electoral board returns to choose the Peronist candidate for the
1989 presidential election showed the charismatic Menem leading
735,799 votes (53 percent) to Cafiero's 641,163 votes (46.2
percent).
   The remaining percentage went to lesser candidates or nullified
ballots.
   The labor-backed Justicialist Party, more commonly known as the
Peronist Party, is Argentina's main opposition group. It made a
comeback in national elections in September last year after five
years of electoral setbacks, capturing the governorships of 17 of
the 22 provinces.
   The party has been split in recent months over the candidacies
of Menem, a fiery orator, and party president Cafiero, a member of
a reform faction. Observers had given Cafiero, the former economy
minister, a slight edge going into the voting.
   Menem, 53, appeared smiling on television late Saturday.
   ``Of course I'm happy. We won. We ran a good race,'' he said.
   In remarks from a downtown hall in the capital Buenos Aires,
Menem dedicated his victory to ``the poorest people, those who need
it the most.''
   Cafiero, 66, whom Menem described as ``my friend ... a loyal man
(who ran) a dignified campaign,'' went on television later Saturday
for about three minutes to congratulate ``Carlos Menem, the
winner.''
   Complete official results were expected Monday.
   Cafiero said he would support Menem in the presidential
elections, dispelling fears in political circles of a split in the
main opposition party, which is favored to defeat the ruling
Radical Civic Party next year.
   Both candidates had favored declaring a moratorium on the
interest portion of Argentina's huge $53 billion foreign debt. The
upcoming campaign is expected to focus on economic issues in
inflation-plagued Argentina.
   In a related development, a flatbed truck carrying some voters
to the polls collided Saturday afternoon with a train at an
unmarked rail crossing in northern Argentina, killing at least 16
people and seriously injuring about 20 others, police and hospital
officials said.
   The accident occurred as the truck was taking voters to a
polling station in El Quebrachal, a village 150 miles southeast of
Salta.
   Up to 4.1 million card-carrying party members were eligible to
vote in the nationwide internal elections. No other incidents were
reported as voter turnouts of up to 65 percent in some interior
provinces were reported.
   The party, founded in the late 1940s behind the populist,
pro-union tendencies of former President Gen. Juan Peron, mainly
attracts working-class adherents, some of whom beat bass drums
fervently at mass rallies. Its politics range from center-left to
rightist, often defying traditional party definitions.
   The governing Radical Civic Union Party of President Raul
Alfonsin elected its candidate, centrist Cordoba provincial Gov.
Eduardo Angeloz, on July 3. By law, Alfonsin cannot run for
re-election.
   The presidential elections are tentatively scheduled for next
May or June, and the president will be elected to a six-year term
beginning in December.
   Alfonsin's election in 1983 ended a harsh nearly eight-year
military dictatorship during which at least 9,000 suspected
leftists were abducted and vanished without a trace during the
``dirty war'' waged by the military against subversion.
</TEXT>
