<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RadioactiveWater     07-09 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radioactive Water,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radioactive Water Released Into Stream At Savannah River Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 360,000 gallons of radioactive water
were released into a stream at the Savannah River Plant,
environmental officials were told Saturday.
   Plant spokesman James Felder, who attributed the release to a
procedural error, said the spill Friday should not affect the
health of the workers or the public around the plant, located in
Aiken County, S.C., across the Savannah River from Augusta.
   South Carolina and Georgia environmental authorities were
notified Saturday morning, although the amounts of the release did
not require notification, The Augusta Chronicle and the Augusta
Herald reported in their combined Sunday editions.
   The water contained two to three millicuries of Cesium-137, a
waste byproduct known to cause cancer. Felder said standards allow
a maximum annual release of 175 millicuries. By the end of May, 50
millicuries had been released at the plant.
   ``It's a very high release for a 12-hour period,'' Felder said.
``But it's well within our guidelines.''
   The contaminated water was expected to reach the Savannah River
about 6:30 p.m. Sunday. Felder said most of Cesium-137 would settle
to the bottom of Four Mile Creek.
</TEXT>
