<1ST_LINE>u i AM-HongKong-Vietnam     07-09 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hong Kong-Vietnam,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Welcomes Vietnam's Initiative On Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has welcomed Vietnam's
willingness to discuss the problem of Vietnamese boat people with
other countries.
   A Hong Kong government statement Friday said the British Embassy
in Hanoi has received an invitation for government officials in
this British colony to visit Vietnam to discuss the issue of the
boat people.
   The statement said the Hong Kong authorities will respond
postively to the invitation but gave no other details.
   It would be very useful to discuss the ``problem with the
Vietnamese authorities and seek their cooperation in stopping the
ouflow (of boat people) and in repatriating those who are not
geninue refugees,'' the statement added.
   In a broadcast made available in Bangkok Friday, Hanoi radio
quoted a Foreign Ministry spokesman as saying that while Vietnam
was ``striving to stop illegal evacuees,'' a number were still
attempting to flee the country.
   ``Vietnam with its humanitarian spirit and mutual understanding
is ready to exchange bilateral views with countries and
international organizations concerned to resolve this problem,''
Hanoi radio quoted the spokesman as saying.
   There are more than 16,000 Vietnamese boat people in Hong Kong.
   In a new policy announced last month, the Hong Kong government
regards all arriving Vietnamese refugees as illegal immigrants
unless they can prove they are fleeing Vietnam because of political
or religious persecution.
   Those found to be illegal immigrants are housed in detention
centers and face repatriation to Vietnam.
</TEXT>
