<HEAD>President to Return Home Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
will return home Monday and his work load will be determined by the
progress of his terminal liver cancer, the government said.
   ``The operation of the government will be left to his
judgment,'' Vice President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount told a news
conference Friday. ``The president's course of action will be
determined by the evolution of his illness. Only when he is back
will we be able to resolve this uncertainty.''
   Castillo has been acting president since Duarte went to the
United States for treatment May 31,. He said the president will be
discharged Saturday from Walter Reed Army Medical Center in
Washington, D.C.
   He said Duarte, 62, would rest Sunday and meet with President
Reagan on Monday before flying to El Salvador on the same U.S. Air
Force hospital plane that took him to Washington. He denied local
news reports that Duarte had decided to resign soon after returning.
   Duarte is undergoing chemotherapy, which is often debilitating.
   Salvadoran officials say he must return to Washington at least
once in the coming months to continue the treatment, which is
intended to slow the cancer's advance. Doctors have given him 18
months to live.
   Communications Minister Roberto Viera told the news conference
reports of Duarte's impending resignation ``are the work of
political sectors that want to give the impression that there's a
power vacuum and division within the government.''
