<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Tempers,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Ambassador Tries to Cool Tempers of Mourners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-Iran, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NAZZAL YOUSSEF</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's ambassador tried
to cool the tempers of mourners at an embassy memorial service for
the 290 people killed when a U.S. warship shot down an Iranian
airliner.
   ``Imam Khomeini becomes the inheritor on earth of any one of us
who is unjustly killed, and only he has the right to decide when
and how to take revenge for those innocent victims,'' Ambassador
Mustafa Foumeni Haeri told hundreds of mourners in the embassy
grounds late Thursday.
   ``Let's not take any hasty action,'' he said in Farsi, the
Iranian language.
   After an hour of weeping conducted by two poets trained in the
mourning ceremony, the crowd chanted: ``Khomeini, Khomeini, we
await your orders! Long life to you, death to Reagan!''
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini is the supreme religious guide for
Iranians and leader of the fundamentalist Islamic revolution that
ousted the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi in February 1979.
   Haeri's appeal for calm coincided with the mood of statements by
Hashemi Rafsanjani, Iran's military commander and parliament
speaker. He told a prayer meeting Friday Iran would not seek
revenge for destruction of the airliner.
   ``The United States is trying to push us to commit the same
crime ... but if we did that the world would turn against us,''
Rafsanjani said. ``That is why we do not push to take revenge. Wise
people understand why we do not take revenge.''
   About 150,000 Iranians live in the United Arab Emirates, across
the southern Persian Gulf from Iran. The memorial service was held
in a mosque attached to the new embassy. Its Persian arches were
festooned with anti-American slogans.
   The ambassador said: ``The mode and style of the revenge will
not be such that the world would condemn it and thus (we) lose the
international sympathy with Iran over the Airbus victims.''
</TEXT>
