<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-USGrain     07-09 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-US Grain,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Rounds Of Talks Fail To Produce Grain Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet negotiators failed to
reach a new grain agreement in a third round of talks which ended
here Friday, Alan F. Holmer, the head of the U.S. team, announced.
   Under a five-year agreement that expires on Sept.30, the Soviets
are committed to buying 9 million tons of U.S. grain a year,
including a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn.
   Holmer, who is deputy U.S. trade representative, said Friday,
``There remain differences on four major areas in the negotiations.
That involves quantities of grain, the pricing of grain, the access
of Soviet ships to U.S. ports and also expanding Soviet exports to
the United States.''
   He refused to say if Moscow wants to decrease its annual
purchasing total.
   The drought in the United States was not a significant issue in
the discussions, Holmer said in reply to a question.
   He said that Thomas Kay, administrator of the Foreign
Agricultural Service, explained to the Soviets ``why we have ample
stocks and production more than meet U.S. domestic needs and export
commitments.''
   ``There are a number of signficiant issues where we would like
to have changes and where they would like to have changes,'' Holmer
said, but added, ``I sense a strong desire on both sides for a new
agreement.''
   The Vienna talks lasted two days. Previous negotiating rounds
took place in Washington in March and in London in May.
   Holmer told reporters no new talks were scheduled, but he
expected negotiations to resume early in September.
   A U.S. delegation official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
put the value of present annual grain sales to the Soviet Union at
about $1.5 billion.
   Holmer said he hoped that before the Soviet negotiations chief,
J. N. Chumakov, goes on vacation on July 25, ``we will know when
and where and whether there will be another round of discussions.''
   Holmer said the Vienna meeting had been useful and ``we made
considerable progress in a number of areas. ... But differences
still remain.''
   The two sides now are now at a stage where they need to review
their positions with their governments, said Holmer, who met
reporters at his hotel.
</TEXT>
