<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Czechoslovak 1stLd-Writethru a0831 07-09 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Czechoslovak, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0831,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Premier Talks of Eventual Red Army Pullouts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 restore paragraph indentation in lead grafs,
INCLUDES ruling out imminent withdrawals. Picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Western reporters ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov on
Friday repeated a Kremlin proposal to withdraw the Red Army from
all foreign territory by the year 2000, apparently ruling out any
imminent pullout of Russian troops from Czechoslovakia and other
Soviet bloc countries.
   The Soviet government chief told Western reporters such moves
could come only in the context of a general withdrawal _ involving
other nations as well as the Soviet Union.
   He also seemed to dash hopes for any rehabilitation soon of
Alexander Dubcek, the former Communist Party leader in
Czechoslovakia.
   His exchanges with the reporters were often acrimonious.
   Ryzhkov confirmed that at the recent Communist Party conference,
Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev stressed the need for
``socialism with a human face.''
   That phrase was used to describe Dubcek's liberal ``Prague
spring'' of 1968, which provoked a Soviet-led Warsaw Pact invasion
in August of that year and cost Dubcek his job as party chief here.
   Western reporters asked Ryzhkov, who attended a three-day
economic conference that ended Thursday, whether the time had not
come for Dubcek to be rehabilitated.
   He replied: ``The rehabilitation of Dubcek, that is a question
for Czechoslovakia. I do not intend to deal with the internal
problems of Czechoslovakia. As far as I know the Czechoslovak party
does not intend to deal with that.''
   Dubcek, now 66, said in an Austrian Television interview
broadcast Thursday that the current leadership in Prague should
adopt Gorbachev's reforms. Most are similar to reforms Dubcek
introduced here 20 years ago.
   Red Army units are stationed in several Soviet bloc countries,
including Czechoslovakia.
   Ryzhkov said his government feels no armies should be on foreign
territory _ U.S., British or Soviet.
   ``Our proposal is this: let us take out all the armies,'' he
said. ``The armies in Czechoslovakia are part of the Warsaw Pact
armies. Let us agree on a radical solution in the West and in the
East.''
   On the theme of ``socialism with a human face,'' Ryzhkov said:
``Socialism must work for man. All our deeds and our reforms must
work for man. We need the participation of man in the whole process.
   ``A great step has been taken toward democratization, toward
glasnost (openness), and that is not possible without man.''
   A Soviet journalist complained about lack of information during
the conference of COMECON, the Soviet bloc equivalent of the
European Economic Community.
   Ryzhkov said he agreed and the practice should be changed
``fundamentally'' because ``95 percent of our the questions
discussed are not in any way secret.''
   He expressed hope the next session in Sofia, Bulgaria would be
different because ``we really have nothing to hide.''
   In reference to communiques issued after Soviet bloc meetings,
which rarely reveal differences of opinion, Ryzhkov declared: ``It
is useless to say that 10 countries have the same opinion. This is
naive.''
</TEXT>
