<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AutoSting     07-09 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sting,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Sting Nets $4 Million In Stolen Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Friday began arresting 135 people
indicted on more than 2,000 felony charges resulting from an
undercover investigation that brought in 380 cars valued at more
than $4 million, authorities said.
   ``We worked 12- to 14-hour days buying cars and returning them
to the insurance companies,'' said Detective Thomas Del Regno of
the Cleveland Police Department.
   The rented garage the undercover operation used held only six
cars, so officers had to turn the vehicles over to insurance
companies quickly, Del Regno said.
   The 16-month undercover operation netted stolen cars from 50
cities as far away as Pennsylvania and Michigan, he said. Cleveland
has one of the 10 highest auto theft rates in the country, he added.
   Del Regno said police arrested 45 to 50 people Friday and served
arrest warrants against 20 other who are already behind bars on
other charges. Arrests are expected to continue during the weekend.
   Those arrested were charged with receiving stolen property and
possession of criminal tools, Cuyahoga County assistant prosecutor
Mary Haas said.
   Two people who allegedly sold police more than 50 cars each face
nearly 100 counts. ``The total number of charges is well over
2,000, but I really haven't kept track,'' she said.
   Del Regno said two undercover police officers set up the
operation by contacting alleged thieves through an informant who
``let it be known that if they came across any cars, we were
available.''
   He said police, who videotaped their car deals in three
Cleveland parking lots, never had to solicit business.
   Thieves often came to sell cars within hours of stealing them,
Del Regno said, ``sometimes even before people knew their cars were
stolen.''
   He said most cars came from young independents known as
``rippers'' who were only interested in ``a quick buck,'' but the
large number of cars some sellers turned over made police suspect
the involvement of several car theft rings.
</TEXT>
