<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Economy     07-09 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Economy,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Reaches 41.3 Percent for First Half of 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 41.3 percent for the
first half of 1988, the business daily El Financiero reported
Friday.
   It tabulated the figures from the Bank of Mexico's announcement
that inflation rose 2 percent in June, slightly above the 1.9
percent increase in May.
   El Financiero's report noted that despite an increase in June,
figures for both months were the lowest registered since November
1981.
   Inflation has been reduced by an Economic Solidarity Pact
designed by the government in December and endorsed by business and
labor. Consumer prices hit a record 159.2 percent last year.
   President Miguel de la Madrid announced the program after
officials became worried that Mexico was on the verge of spiraling
into hyperinflation, a problem that has plagued other Latin
American countries.
   Critics say the pact was intended to artificially control
inflation before Wednesday's general elections.
   The president concludes his six-year term on Nov. 30, with his
successor virtually certain to be Carlos Salinas de Gortari of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party that has governed Mexico since
1929.
   The budget and planning secretary, Pedro Aspe, said Wednesday
that it will be up to the next administration to decide if the pact
continues past November.
   He told reporters that the agreement remains in effect at least
through August and that its status for the last three months of de
la Madrid's term won't be determined until the middle of next month.
   A Bank of Mexico report issued late Thursday said a beef
shortage in turn prompted increases in prices of chicken and pork
and so contributed to higher prices, as did a longer than usual dry
season that caused increases in fruit and vegetable prices.
   Among other factors in June's consumer price rises were
residential rents, which were 4.3 percent higher and represented
the largest single increase, the central bank said. Prices on basic
foods and other essentials rose .4 percent.
   Of the 35 cities checked, the highest increases were 4.3 percent
in Zamora, in western Michoacan state, and 2.5 percent in Toluca,
40 miles west of Mexico City.
   The bank's report said the solidarity pact ``continues being
successful in holding down the inflationary process.''
   A key component of the inflation-fighting program is a freeze on
the minimum wage, prices of government-regulated goods and services
and the exchange rate of the peso currency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880709-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs     07-09 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs,0663</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-four men survived the Piper
Alpha oil rig fire by leaping into the burning sea in the dark, but
they had to leave behind more than 100 colleagues trapped and
screaming for air in the inferno.
   ``I am one of the lucky ones,'' Harry Calder said in an
interview Friday. ``I am pretty sore, I am badly bruised and my
hands are burned. But at least I'm alive. I have lost a lot of
friends.''
   Seventeen bodies have been found and 166 men are presumed dead
in the North Sea oil field where the rig exploded Wednesday night.
   At least 100 men died screaming for help, trapped in their
sleeping quarters after surviving the first explosion, said Calder,
a 35-year-old helicopter landing officer.
   The workers were in the smoke-filled galley of the platform,
which was plunged into darkness when the emergency lighting failed,
he said in an interview Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Aegis air defense system, used by the
cruiser Vincennes last week to track and shoot down an Iranian
passenger jet, may not have been adequately tested before it was
deployed, according to a classified review by a congressional
watchdog agency.
   The General Accounting Office study concluded that the $1
billion system has not proven its ability to discriminate among
targets, said congressional sources who have seen the document.
They spoke Friday on condition they not be named.
   The GAO review started last year and did not mention last week's
destruction of Iran Air flight 655 that killed all 290 people
aboard. The Vincennes fired at the airliner after mistaking it for
an Iranian F-14.
   Pentagon officials have said the Aegis system was not
malfunctioning. A ``minor degradation'' of the Aegis radar was
repaired before the ship entered the Persian Gulf last month, they
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge's order giving Oliver L. North broader
access to secret government documents for his defense strongly
raises the possibility he won't be tried on the main charges of the
Iran-Contra indictment.
   But the order issued Friday by U.S. District Judge Gerhard A.
Gesell clears the way for the fired White House aide to go to trial
at least on charges he lied to cover up his activities and
personally gained from his involvement in the Iran-Contra affair.
   The judge's order scheduling the trial for Sept. 20 set the
stage for the proceeding to take place in the middle of the fall
presidential campaign.
   In addition to fixing the trial date, Gesell ruled that North is
entitled to use highly classified documents that might show the
covert activities that are the basis of the Iran-Contra conspiracy
charge were authorized by the Reagan administration.
   The judge noted that some highly sensitive portions of documents
in the prosecution's case that government security experts want
deleted ``tended to exonerate North of guilt on certain charges.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legal Services Corp. is defending its
chairman against congressional allegations that he improperly used
government funds for presidential politics, personal business and
to help destroy the agency.
   The corporation, in a prepared statement issued late Friday,
said it has uncovered no evidence ``that would lend credence to
insinuations of misappropriation'' by W. Clark Durant III.
   Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., outlined the allegations and
called for the resignation of Durant, who has served as chairman of
the agency's board since December 1984 and was an adviser to Rep.
Jack Kemp's failed presidential campaign.
   ``He's been undermining the Legal Services Corporation by
personal and political activities ... at the expense of the
taxpayers,'' Morrison charged.
   Rep. Robert W. Kastenmeier, D-Wis., chairman of the House
Judiciary subcommittee on courts, civil liberties and the
