price trends</NOTE>
<HEAD>Some Commodity Markets Cooling Down After Ride On Drought Train</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   After weeks of playing follow-the-soybeans, traders in a number
of commodity markets are looking elsewhere for signals on whether
to buy or sell.
   Some of these markets, such as gold and sugar, have only a
marginal interest in grain and soybean prices to begin with.
   Others _ cotton in particular _ have almost no real relationship
to soybeans and are cooling down after a frantic ride on the
drought train, courtesy of market speculators.
   The Midwestern drought remains the dominant influence in the
grain and soybean markets and in the livestock markets, where the
price of feed grain is directly related to production costs.
   But the drought's diminishing impact on the prices of other
commodities illustrates how the powerful psychology of a runaway
market can sweep others along with it _ until the facts get in the
way.
   ``In the end, the fundamentals always reign supreme,'' said
Ernest Simon, cotton specialist with Prudential Bache Securities
Inc. in New York.
   In the cotton market, the fundamentals include the Agriculture
Department's prediction of a 5.6 million-bale surplus on July 31,
the end of the current marketing year, and a whopping 6.8
million-bale surplus a year later. There is nearly enough cotton in
storage to fulfill all of next year's expected domestic demand,
twice as much as experts consider adequate.
   Before the drought began, the USDA estimated 1988-89 cotton
production at 14 million bales. Analysts say even severe drought
damage wouldn't reduce the oversupply.
   ``We could lose 2{ million bales and not be hurt,'' said Ed
Whitten, cotton specialist with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in New York.
   So why did near-month cotton futures follow the soybean market's
sharp springtime surge, rallying from about 60 cents a pound on
April 15 to almost 70 cents by June 20?
   ``Cotton very often is called soybean's little brother,''
Whitten said. ``It follows it slavishly.''
   Added Rich Cantor, cotton analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc.: ``It wasn't so much the fabulous buying that brought
the prices up, it was that you didn't have anybody willing to sell
it. That allowed the speculative element to move prices higher in
tandem with the other markets.''
   Cotton futures prices have since come back down to around 60
cents a pound.
   ``People finally became convinced the fundamentals had been
ignored too long, said Simon.
   The inflation-sensitive gold market followed a similar, albeit
shorter path. In early June, gold for August delivery surged above
its recent $440-to-$460 trading range to more than $470 a troy
ounce. The accepted explanation was that traders feared the sharp
rise in grain prices would lead to greater inflation.
   Those worries were quickly calmed by economists, who pointed out
the miniscule impact of food prices on the Consumer Price Index,
and gold prices eased back into their well-worn trading range.
   ``The soybean market and the rally we had in previous weeks
certainly constituted a psychological inducement to rally the
precious metals. But in general you have to keep the advance in
perspective,'' said George Anagnos, metals analyst with Thomson
McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``The gold market indicated ... that food-inspired increases
alone were not going to boost inflation rates to dangerously high
levels.''
   In fact, commodity markets almost never take their direction
from a single source and single-day moves often have no easy
explanation, said Steve Chronowitz, director of futures research
for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   ``The media naturally wants to know why gold is up a dollar
today or why it's down a dollar,'' he said. ``Sometimes there is no
reason. But when they're at a loss to explain a move, analysts will
tend to tie it to something else.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880709-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-InflationOutlook Adv11   07-09 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Inflation Outlook, Adv 11,0745</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday July 11</NOTE>
<HEAD>With Unemployment Down, Pressure Building For Bigger Wage Demands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a long break from inflation, the United
States is entering the early phase of a new cycle of quickly rising
prices, some economists now say.
   A resurgence of inflation may take a year or more, but if it
does set in again, it might not be stoppable by anything short of a
government-induced recession, these economists say.
   The U.S. economy has defied expectations of trouble many times
before during this record, nearly 6-year-long expansion, and it may
do so again.
   The bond market, which is the most sensitive barometer of
inflation, has been fairly calm lately. Interest rates are down
from their highs of late May.
   But inflation alarms went up Friday when the government reported
that the nation's civilian unemployment rate fell to 5.3 percent in
June, its lowest level in 14 years.
   The report added to inflationary concerns caused by the
export-led boom in manufacturing, which has resulted in bottlenecks
and spotty shortages. Meanwhile, industrial commodity prices have
jumped 25 percent in the past two years.
   A low jobless rate means employers are having trouble finding
and keeping qualified workers. By the laws of supply and demand,
that means wages could start rising rapidly.
   American workers have been tolerating low wage increases for so
long that some economists have concluded that they have permanently
lowered their expectations.
   In the last year, for example, wages rose 3.2 percent, failing
to keep up with a roughly 4.4 percent increase in consumer prices.
   In June, the average hourly wage rate in private industry was no
higher than the May rate: $9.27 an hour.
   At some point, though, the tables are likely to turn. Workers
will be in such demand that they will be able to insist on pay
increases that help them catch up, or at least stop falling farther
behind.
   And since wage costs account for about 55 percent of the cost of
production, big pay increases could push the economy into an
inflationary cycle.
   Kenneth Goldstein, labor economist for the Conference Board,
says the ``startling'' June jobless rate is probably a quirk caused
by an underestimate of the size of the labor force. He says there
is no strong evidence of a tight labor market.
   But Lacy Hunt, chief economist of the CM&M Group, said, ``Wages
are slow to react, but when they turn, they turn decisively and
rapidly and then they're hard to contain.''
   Hunt was the most pessimistic on inflation of 32 economists
included in a forecasting chart published last week by the Wall
Street Journal, predicting an inflation rate of 6.8 percent in the
first half of 1989.
   Still, even economists who are relatively optimistic say the
situation is worsening. ``There are a lot of little pieces of
evidence that inflation is starting to accelerate,'' said Nancy
Lazar, an economist for C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc.
   The drop in the dollar from its 1985 peak has created strong
demand for American-made products and strained the production
capacity of U.S. factories. The dollar's recent rise could take off
some of the edge, but it may not last.
   Adding to the strain is the huge federal budget deficit, which
has become more of a problem now that the economy is already in
danger of overheating. When the government spends more than it
takes in, it can overstimulate an economy that is barely coping
with strong private demand.
   Hunt said the government should try to slash the federal deficit
to less than $100 billion in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, but
realistically expects the gap to spread to as much as $180 billion.
   With government spending out of control, the only remedy for
inflation is on the supply side. The Federal Reserve, not known for
its finesse, would have to cool off the economy by jacking up
interest rates, very likely choking off the historic expansion,
Hunt said.
   ``We're in the early stages of an insurgence of inflation,''
Hunt said. ``This is the equivalent of the Vietnam inflation of the
mid-'60s, the early stages of the Nixon inflation of late '72, and
the early stages of the Carter inflation around 1977 or 1978.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday July 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
