<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     07-09 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low Unemployment Rate Raises Inflation Fears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Droves of teen-agers on summer employment rolls helped push the
nation's unemployment rate to a 14-year low in June, but the news
rekindled inflation fears and sent stock and bond prices tumbling.
   The Labor Department reported Friday before trading began on
Wall Street that the unemployment rate for June stood at 5.3
percent.
   The unexpectedly strong report sent the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials down 16.54 points to a close at 2,106.15 in light
trading.
   Concern that inflation might rise as the economy heats up also
rippled through the credit markets, where the Treasury's bellwether
30-year issue fell about $10 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield
jumped to 9.09 percent from 9.00 percent late Thursday.
   But the unemployment report was welcomed in the currency
markets, where the dollar jumped despite central bank intervention.
   Traders reasoned that a big reported rise in manufacturing
employment was an indication that exports remained strong, which
could help shrink the trade deficit and support the dollar.
   The Labor Department said the sharp drop from May's 5.6 percent
jobless rate was caused by a seasonally adjusted surge of 820,000
people _ three-fourths of them youths 16 to 24 years old _ onto the
nation's payrolls.
   Joblessness among black youths plummeted more than 6 percentage
points to its lowest level on record.
   Analysts had anticipated a large increase this year in the
number of available summer jobs, especially in the tourist
industry, as foreigners taking advantage of the devalued dollar
flock to the United States for their vacations.
   In other economic developments Friday:
   _The Federal Reserve Board reported that Americans increased
their installment borrowing at a modest annual rate of 4.6 percent
in May, as growth in consumer credit slowed from the rapid
expansion of earlier this year.
   Consumers took out $2.42 billion more in credit than they paid
off in May, compared with net growth of $3.85 billion in April.
   _Oil futures turned mixed in moderate trading as dealers
reassessed the impact of the recent North Sea oil rig explosion on
petroleum supplies and prospects for an emergency OPEC meeting
diminished.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for August
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
fell 37 cents to $15.46 per 42-gallon barrel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880709-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     07-09 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures gave up some of their recent gains
as dealers reassessed the impact of the recent North Sea oil rig
explosion on petroleum supplies and prospects for an emergency OPEC
meeting diminished.
   ``It may be a case of calmer heads prevailing today,'' Peter
Beutel, an oil analyst with Elders Futures Inc., said of Friday's
trading session.
   Prices for petroleum futures and contracts for refined products
had soared on Thursday as traders reacted to reports that the
Scotland rig explosion would affect about 12 percent of total North
Sea production, or as much as 300,000 barrels of oil per day.
   In addition, there was concern that the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting countries might call an emergency meeting to
discuss overproduction among some of its members.
   ``I think they over-reacted to the effects of the platform fire
and they realized it really didn't mean that much ... and the gains
were given back,'' said James R. Steele, an energy analsyt with
Refco Inc. ``I think the market also realized there wasn't going to
be an emergency meeting.''
   As a result, he said, Friday's trading was highlighted by
profit-taking and a general correction from Thursday's overbought
condition.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for August
delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude oil fell 37 cents to
$15.46 per 42-gallon barrel after closing 47 cents higher on
Thursday. The contract had traded well above $16 during that
session.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, home heating oil
fell 0.90 cent to 43.39 cents a gallon.
   Unleaded gasoline rose 0.05 cent to 53.17 cents a gallon.
Analysts attributed the slight rise to reports of strong seasonal
demand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
